 March 2020\n|2\n|2\n|0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Ouargla Province|Ouargla]]\n|30 March 2020\n|2\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Tissemsilt Province|Tissemsilt]]\n|19 March 2020\n|2\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Bechar Province|B\u00e9char]]\n|3 April 2020\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Illizi Province|Illizi]]\n|31 March 2020\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Laghouat Province|Laghouat]]\n|24 March 2020\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Mila Province|Mila]]\n|4 April 2020\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Tiaret Province|Tiaret]]\n|2 April 2020\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|-\n\n!'''Total'''\n! \n!1,251\n!130\n!90\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\" |<small>Latest update: 4 April 2020<ref>{{cite web|title=COVID-19 : Carte \u00e9pid\u00e9miologique|url=http://covid19.sante.gov.dz/carte/|language=fr-DZ|publisher=Ministry of Health, Population, and Hospital Reform|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref></small>\n|}\n\n==See also== \n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Algeria]]\n* [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation and tourism]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tunisia}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Morocco}}\n{{#related:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Algeria]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Algeria]]\n[[Category:2020 in Algeria]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Africa]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Africa]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Algeria]]\n", "name_user": "Vegetableroof", "label": "safe", "comment": "Insert bar plots.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Algeria"}
{"title_page": "Boring Billion", "text_new": "{{short description|Between 1.8 and 0.8 billion years ago}}\n{{Life timeline}}\nThe '''Boring Billion''', otherwise known as the '''Barren Billion''', the '''Dullest Time in Earth's History''', and '''Earth's Middle Ages''', is the time period between 1.8 and 0.8 billion years ago (Gya) spanning the middle [[Proterozoic]] [[eon (geology)|eon]], characterized by more or less [[tectonic]] stability, climatic stasis, and stalled biological evolution. It is bordered by two different oxygenation and glacial events, but the Boring Billion itself had very low oxygen levels and no evidence of glaciation.\n\nThe oceans may have been oxygen- and nutrient-poor and sulfidic ([[euxinia]]), populated by mainly [[anoxygenic photosynthesis|anoxygenic]] [[cyanobacteria]], a type of photosynthetic bacteria which uses [[hydrogen sulfide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S) instead of water and produces [[sulfur]] instead of oxygen. This is known as a [[Canfield ocean]]. Such composition may have caused the oceans to be black- and milky-turquoise instead of blue.\n\nDespite such adverse conditions, [[eukaryote]]s may have evolved around the beginning of the Boring Billion, and adopted several novel adaptations, such as various [[organelle]]s and possibly [[evolution of sexual reproduction|sexual reproduction]], and diversified into [[plant]]s, [[animal]]s, and [[fungi]]. Such advances may have been important precursors to the evolution of large, complex life later in the [[Cambrian explosion]]. However, [[prokaryotic]] cyanobacteria were the dominant lifeforms during this time, and likely supported an energy-poor [[food-web]] with a small number of [[protist]]s at the [[apex predator|apex level]]. The land was likely inhabited by prokaryotic cyanobacteria and eukaryotic proto-[[lichen]]s, the latter more successful here probably due to the greater availability of nutrients than offshore ocean waters.\n\n==Description==\nIn 1995, geologists [[Roger Buick]], [[Davis Des Marais]], and [[Andrew Knoll]] reviewed the apparent lack of major biological, geological, and climatic events during the [[Mesoproterozoic]] [[era]] 1.6 to 1 billion years ago (Gya), and, thus, described it as \"the dullest time in Earth's history\".<ref name=Buick1995>{{Cite journal|title = Stable isotopic compositions of carbonates from the Mesoproterozoic Bangemall group, northwestern Australia|journal = Chemical Geology|year=1995|pages = 153\u2013171|volume = 123|issue = 1\u20134|doi = 10.1016/0009-2541(95)00049-R|pmid = 11540130|first = R.|last = Buick|first2 = D. J.|last2 = Des Marais|first3 = A. H.|last3 = Knoll|authorlink3=Andrew Knoll|bibcode = 1995ChGeo.123..153B}}</ref> The term \"Boring Billion\" was coined by paleontologist [[Martin Brasier]] to refer to the time between about 2 and 1 Gya, which was characterized by geochemical stasis and glacial stagnation.{{sfn|Brasier|2012|loc=p. 211}} In 2013, geochemist [[Grant Young (geochemist)|Grant Young]] used the term \"Barren Billion\" to refer to a period of apparent glacial stagnation and lack of carbon isotope excursions from 1.8 to 0.8 Gya.<ref name=:4/> In 2014, geologists [[Peter Cawood]] and [[Chris Hawkesworth]] called the time between 1.7 and 0.75 Gya \"Earth's Middle Ages\" due to a lack of evidence of tectonic movement.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nThe Boring Billion is now largely cited as spanning about 1.8 to 0.8 Gya, contained within the [[Proterozoic]] [[eon (geology)|eon]], mainly the Mesoproterozoic. The Boring Billion is characterized by geological, climatic, and by-and-large evolutionary stasis, with low nutrient abundance.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=Mukherjee2018/><ref name=Holland2006/><ref name=Peng2019/>\n\nIn the time leading up to the Boring Billion, Earth experienced the [[Great Oxygenation Event]] due to the evolution of [[oxygenic photosynthesis|oxygenic photosynthetic]] [[cyanobacteria]], and the resultant [[Huronian glaciation]] ([[Snowball Earth]]), formation of the [[UV]]-blocking [[ozone layer]], and oxidation of several metals.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book| year = 2011| last = Lenton| first = T.| last2 = Watson| first2 = A.| pages = 242\u2013261| doi = 10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199587049.003.0013|title = Revolutions that made the Earth|isbn = 9780199587049}}</ref> Boring Billion oxygen levels dramatically dropped.<ref name=\":10\" /> It was ended by the breakup of the supercontinent [[Rodinia]], a second oxygenation event, and another Snowball Earth in the [[Cryogenian]] period.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|title = Earth's middle age|journal = Geology|date = 2014-06-01|issn = 0091-7613|pages = 503\u2013506|volume = 42|issue = 6|doi = 10.1130/G35402.1|language = en|first = Peter A.|last = Cawood|first2 = Chris J.|last2 = Hawkesworth|bibcode = 2014Geo....42..503C}}</ref><ref name=Brooke2014/>\n\n== Tectonic stasis ==\n{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=Paleoglobe NO 1590 mya-vector-colors.svg|image2=Rodinia reconstruction.jpg|footer=Reconstruction of [[Columbia (supercontinent)|Columbia]] (above, 1.6 Gya) and [[Rodinia]] after break-up (below, 0.75 Gya)}}\nThe evolution of Earth's [[biosphere]], atmosphere, and [[hydrosphere]] has long been linked to the [[supercontinent cycle]], where the continents aggregate and then drift apart. The Boring Billion saw the evolution of two supercontinents: [[Columbia (supercontinent)|Columbia]] (or Nuna) and [[Rodinia]].<ref name=Evans2013/>\n\nThe supercontinent Columbia formed between 2.0 and 1.7&nbsp;Ga and remained intact until at least 1.3&nbsp;Ga. Geological and [[Paleomagnetism|paleomagnetic]] evidence suggest that Columbia underwent only minor changes to form the supercontinent Rodinia from 1.1 to 0.9&nbsp;Ga. [[Palaeogeography|Paleogeographic]] reconstructions suggest that the supercontinent assemblage was located in [[equator]]ial and [[Temperate climate|temperate]] climate zones, and there is little or no evidence for continental fragments in [[polar region]]s.<ref name=Evans2013>{{Cite journal|title = Reconstructing pre-Pangean supercontinents|year=2013|journal = Geological Society of America Bulletin|pages = 1735\u20131751|volume = 125|issue = 11\u201312|doi = 10.1130/b30950.1|first = D. A. D.|last = Evans|bibcode = 2013GSAB..125.1735E}}</ref>\n\nDue to the lack of evidence of sediment build-up (on passive margins) which would occur as a result of [[rift]]ing,<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Passive margins through earth history|journal = Earth-Science Reviews|date = 2008-12-01|pages = 1\u201326|volume = 91|issue = 1\u20134|doi = 10.1016/j.earscirev.2008.08.001|first = Dwight C.|last = Bradley|bibcode = 2008ESRv...91....1B|url = https://zenodo.org/record/1258907}}</ref> the supercontinent probably did not break up, and rather was simply an assemblage of juxtaposed proto-continents and [[craton]]s. There is no evidence of rifting until the formation of Rodinia, 1.25 Gya in North Laurentia, and 1 Gya in East [[Baltica]] and South [[Siberia]].<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\" /> However, breakup did not occur until 0.75 Gya, marking the end of the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":1\" /> This tectonic stasis may have been related in ocean and atmospheric chemistry.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = The boring billion? \u2013 Lid tectonics, continental growth and environmental change associated with the Columbia supercontinent|journal = Geoscience Frontiers|year=2013 |df=dmy-all |pages = 681\u2013691|volume = 4|series = Thematic Section: Antarctica \u2013 A window to the far off land|issue = 6|doi = 10.1016/j.gsf.2013.05.004|first = N. M. W.|last = Roberts}}</ref><ref name=Holland2006>{{Cite journal|title = The oxygenation of the atmosphere and oceans|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|date = 2006-06-29|issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 1578726|pmid = 16754606|pages = 903\u2013915|volume = 361|issue = 1470|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2006.1838|language = en|first = Heinrich D.|last = Holland}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIt is possible the [[asthenosphere]]\u2014the molten layer of Earth's [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] that tectonic plates essentially float and move around upon\u2014was too hot to sustain modern plate tectonics at this time. Instead of vigorous plate recycling at [[Subduction|subduction zones]], plates were linked together for billions of years until the mantle cooled off enough. The onset of this component of plate tectonics may have been aided by the cooling and thickening of the [[Crust (geology)|crust]] that, once initiated, caused plate subduction to be anomalously strong, occurring at the end of the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNonetheless, major [[magma]]tic events still occurred, namely the formation (via [[magma plume]]) of the {{cvt|220,000|km2|mi2|adj=on}} central Australian [[Musgrave Province]] from 1.22 to 1.12 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=W.|last=Gorczyk|first2=H.|last2=Smithies|first3=F.|last3=Korhonen|first4=H.|last4=Howard|first5=R. Q.|last5=de Gromard|year=2015|title=Ultra-hot Mesoproterozoic evolution of intracontinental central Australia|journal=Geoscience Frontiers|volume=6|issue=1|pages=23\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.gsf.2014.03.001}}</ref> and the {{cvt|2,700,000|km2|mi2}} Canadian [[Mackenzie Large Igneous Province]] 1.27 Gya;<ref>{{cite journal|first=S. E.|last=Bryan|first2=L.|last2=Ferrari|year=2013|title=Large igneous provinces and silicic large igneous provinces: Progress in our understanding over the last 25 years|journal=GSA Bulletin|volume=125|issue=7\u20138|page=1055<!--only citing this page-->|doi=10.1130/B30820.1}}</ref> and plate tectonics were still active enough to build mountains, with several [[orogenies]] known from the time, such as the [[Grenville orogeny]].<ref name=\"one\">{{Cite book |last=Tollo |first=R. P. |first2=L.|last2=Corriveau |first3=J.|last3=McLelland |first4=M. J.|last4=Bartholomew  |year=2004 |chapter=Proterozoic tectonic evolution of the Grenville orogen in North America: An introduction |editor1-last=Tollo |editor1-first=R. P. |editor2-first=L. |editor2-last=Corriveau |editor3-first=J. |editor3-last=McLelland |editor4-first=M. J. |editor4-last=Bartholomew |title=Proterozoic tectonic evolution of the Grenville orogen in North America |series=Geological Society of America Memoir |volume=197 |pages=1\u201318 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uT4HISRCon8C&pg=PA1&q  |isbn=978-0-8137-1197-3 }}</ref>\n\n== Climatic stability ==\n[[File:Mesoproterozoic temperature.jpg|thumb|300px|Graph showing average temperatures during the Mesoproterozoic. Blue line uses CO<sub>2</sub> concentration 5 times modern day, red line 10 times, and red dot shows average temperature range at the tropics]]\nThere is little evidence of significant climatic variability during this time period.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|title = Precambrian supercontinents, glaciations, atmospheric oxygenation, metazoan evolution and an impact that may have changed the second half of Earth history|journal = Geoscience Frontiers|year=2013|pages = 247\u2013261|volume = 4|issue = 3|doi = 10.1016/j.gsf.2012.07.003|first = Grant M.|last = Young}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title = A billion years of environmental stability and the emergence of eukaryotes: New data from northern Australia |last = Brasier |first = M.D. |year= 1998 |journal = Geology|doi =10.1130/0091-7613(1998)026<0555:ABYOES>2.3.CO;2 |pmid = 11541449 |volume=26 |issue = 6|pages = 555\u2013558 |bibcode = 1998Geo....26..555B }}</ref>  Climate was likely not primarily dictated by solar luminosity, because, if it were, all water on the planet would have been locked up in ice\u2014which was not the case according to the fossil record\u2014<ref name=Veizer2005/> because the sun was 5\u201318% less luminous than today ([[faint young Sun paradox]]).<ref name=Fiorella2017>{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Fiorella|first2=N.|last2=Sheldon|year=2017|title=Equable end Mesoproterozoic climate in the absence of high CO2|journal=Geology|volume=45|issue=3|pages=231\u2013234|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/311885954|doi=10.1130/G38682.1}}</ref> In fact, the Boring Billion is unique in a sense that it seems to lack any evidence of significant periods of prolonged glaciations, which can be observed in regular periodicity in other parts of Earth's geologic history.<ref name=Veizer2005/> High CO<sub>2</sub> could not have been a main driver because levels would have needed to be 30 to 100 times greater than pre-[[Industrial Revolution|industrial]] levels<ref name=Fiorella2017/> and produced substantial [[ocean acidification]]<ref name=Veizer2005/> to prevent ice formation, which also did not occur. Mesoproterozoic CO<sub>2</sub> levels may have been comparable to those of the [[Phanerozoic]] eon, perhaps 7 to 10 times today's levels.<ref name=Kah2007>{{cite journal|first=L. C.|last=Kah|first2=R.|last2=Riding|year=2007|title=Mesoproterozoic carbon dioxide levels inferred from calcified cyanobacteria|journal=Geology|volume=35|issue=9|pages=799\u2013802|doi=10.1130/G23680A.1|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f7e26bb7a9aee8909f9d583c86ea3d4daa7a4609}}</ref> The first record of ice from this time period was reported in 2020 from the 1 Ga Scottish [[Diabaig Formation]] in the [[Torridon Group]], where [[dropstone]] formations were likely formed by debris from [[ice rafting]]; the area, then situated between [[35th parallel south|35]]\u2013[[50th parallel south|50]]\u00b0S, was a (possibly upland) lake which is thought to have frozen over in the winter and melted in the summer, rafting occurring in the spring melt.<ref>{{cite journal|first=A.|last=Hartley|first2=B.|last2=Kurjanski|first3=J.|last3=Pugsley|first4=J.|last4=Armstrong|year=2020|title=Ice-rafting in lakes in the early Neoproterozoic: dropstones in the Diabaig Formation, Torridon Group, NW Scotland|journal=Scottish Journal of Geology|doi=10.1144/sjg2019-017}}</ref>\n\nA higher abundance of other greenhouse gases, namely methane produced by prokaryotes, may have compensated for the low CO<sub>2</sub> levels; a largely ice-free world may have been achieved with a methane concentration of 140 [[parts per million]] (ppm).<ref name=Kah2007/><ref name=Fiorella2017/> However, [[methanogenic]] prokaryotes could not have produced so much methane, implying some other greenhouse gas, probably [[nitrous oxide]], was elevated, perhaps to 3 ppm (10 times today's levels). Based on presumed greenhouse gas concentrations, equatorial temperatures during the Mesoproterozoic may have been about {{cvt|295\u2013300|K|C F}}, in the tropics {{cvt|290|K|C F}}, at 60\u00b0 {{cvt|265\u2013280|K|C F}}, and the poles {{cvt|250\u2013275|K|C F}};<ref>{{cite journal|first=M. T.|last=Hren|first2=N. D.|last2=Sheldon|year=2020|title=Terrestrial microbialites provide constraints on the mesoproterozoic atmosphere|journal=The Depositional Record|volume=6|pages=4\u201320|doi=10.1002/dep2.79}}</ref> and the global average temperature about {{cvt|19|C|F}}, which is 4&nbsp;\u00b0C (7.2&nbsp;\u00b0F) warmer than today. Temperatures at the poles were estimated to have dropped below freezing in winter, allowing for temporary sea ice formation and snowfall, but there were likely no permanent ice sheets.<ref name=Peng2019>{{cite journal|first=L.|last=Peng|first2=L.|last2=Yonggang|first3=H.|last3=Yongyun|first4=Y.|last4=Yun|first5=S. A.|last5=Pisarevsky|year=2019|title=Warm Climate in the \"Boring Billion\" Era|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=93|pages=40\u201343|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.14239}}</ref>\n\nIt has also been proposed that, because the intensity of [[cosmic ray]]s has been shown to be positively correlated to cloud cover, and cloud cover reflects light back out into space and reduces global temperatures, lower rates of bombardment during this time due to reduced star formation in the galaxy caused less cloud cover and stayed glaciation events, maintaining a warm climate.<ref name=Veizer2005>{{Cite journal|title = Celestial Climate Driver: A Perspective from Four Billion Years of the Carbon Cycle|url = https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/GC/article/view/2691|journal = Geoscience Canada|year=2005 |df=dmy-all |issn = 1911-4850|volume = 32|issue = 1|first = J.|last = Veizer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Shaviv| first = Nir J.| year=2003 |df=dmy-all| title = The spiral structure of the Milky Way, cosmic rays, and ice age epochs on Earth| journal = New Astronomy| volume = 8| issue = 1| pages = 39\u201377| doi = 10.1016/S1384-1076(02)00193-8| arxiv = astro-ph/0209252| bibcode = 2003NewA....8...39S}}</ref> Also, some combination of weathering intensity which would have reduced CO<sub>2</sub> levels by oxidation of exposed metals, cooling of the [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] and reduced [[geothermal heat]] and volcanism, and increasing solar intensity and solar heat may have reached an equilibrium barring ice formation.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nConversely, glacial movements over a billion years ago may not have left many remnants today, and an apparent lack of evidence could simply be due to the incompleteness of the fossil record rather than absence. Further, the low oxygen and solar intensity levels may have prevented the formation of the [[ozone layer]], preventing [[greenhouse gas]]ses from being trapped in the atmosphere and heating the Earth via the [[greenhouse effect]], which would have caused glaciation.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Glacio-epochs and the supercontinent cycle after \u223c 3.0&nbsp;Ga: Tectonic boundary conditions for glaciation|journal = Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|year=2008 |df=dmy-all |pages = 89\u2013129|volume = 258|issue = 1\u20132|doi = 10.1016/j.palaeo.2007.09.021|first = N.|last = Eyles}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Palaeoclimates: the first two billion years|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|year=2006 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 1868609|pmid = 16754607|pages = 917\u2013929|volume = 361|issue = 1470|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2006.1839|first = J. F.|last = Kasting|first2 = S.|last2 = Ono}}</ref> However, not much oxygen is necessary to sustain the ozone layer, and levels during the Boring Billion may have been high enough for it,<ref>{{cite book|first=D. C.|last=Catling|first2=J. F.|last2=Kasting|year=2017|title=Atmospheric Evolution on Inhabited and Lifeless Worlds|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=291|isbn=978-1-316-82452-8}}</ref> though the Earth may still have been more heavily bombarded by [[UV radiation]] than today.<ref name=Campesi2013/>\n\n==Oceanic composition==\nThe oceans seem to have had low concentrations of key nutrients thought to be necessary for complex life, namely [[molybdenum]], iron, [[nitrogen]], and [[phosphorus]], in large part due to a lack of oxygen and resultant [[oxidation]] necessary for these [[geochemical cycle]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Anbar| first = A. D.| last2 = Knoll| first2 = A. H.| year=2002 |df=dmy-all| title = Proterozoic Ocean Chemistry and Evolution: A Bioinorganic Bridge?| journal = Science| volume = 297| issue = 5584| pages = 1137\u20131142| doi = 10.1126/science.1069651| issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 12183619| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1137A| citeseerx = 10.1.1.615.3041}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| authorlink1=Katja Fennel| last = Fennel| first = K.| last2 = Follows| first2 = M| last3 = Falkowski| first3 = P. G.| year=2005| title = The co-evolution of the nitrogen, carbon and oxygen cycles in the Proterozoic ocean| journal = American Journal of Science| volume = 305| issue = 6\u20138| pages = 526\u2013545| doi = 10.2475/ajs.305.6-8.526| issn = 0002-9599| bibcode = 2005AmJS..305..526F}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=M. A.|last=Kipp|first2=E. E.|last2=St\u00fceken|year=2017|title=Biomass recycling and Earth's early phosphorus cycle|journal=Science Advances|volume=3|issue=11|pages=eaao4795|doi=10.1126/sciadv.aao4795|pmid=29202032|pmc=5706743}}</ref> However, nutrients were more abundant in terrestrial environments, such as lakes or nearshore environments closer to continental runoff.<ref name=Parnell2015>{{cite journal|first=J.|last=Parnell|first2=S.|last2=Sprinks|first3=S.|last3=Andrews|first4=W.|last4=Thayalan|first5=S.|last5=Bowden|year=2015|title=High Molybdenum availability for evolution in a Mesoproterozoic lacustrine environment|journal=Nature Communications|volume=6|issue=6996|pages=6996|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/276921766|doi=10.1038/ncomms7996|pmid=25988499}}</ref>\n\nIn general, the oceans may have had an oxygenated surface layer, a sulfidic middle layer,<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\"/> and suboxic bottom layer.<ref name=Slack2009/><ref name=DeBaar1988/> The predominantly sulfidic composition may have caused the oceans to be a black- and milky-turquoise color instead of blue.<ref>{{cite journal|first=V. A.|last=Gallardo|first2=C.|last2=Espinoza|year=2008|title=Evolution of ocean color|journal=Proceedings of the International Society for Optical Engineering|volume=7097|pages=1\u20137|doi=10.1117/12.794742|bibcode=2008SPIE.7097E..0GG|url=https://www.comlsecretariat.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Gallardo-Espinoza-paper-on-the-evolution-of-ocean-color.pdf|series=Instruments, Methods, and Missions for Astrobiology XI|editor1-last=Hoover|editor1-first=Richard B|editor2-last=Levin|editor2-first=Gilbert V|editor3-last=Rozanov|editor3-first=Alexei Y|editor4-last=Davies|editor4-first=Paul C}}</ref>\n\n===Oxygen===\n[[File:Evolution Of Atmosferic Oxygen.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Partial pressure]], in [[standard atmosphere (unit)|atm]], of atmospheric oxygen over the last 3.85 Ga (upper and lower estimates)]]\nEarth's geologic record indicates two events associated with significant increases in oxygen levels on Earth, with one occurring between 2.4 and 2.1 Gya, known as the Great Oxygenation Event, and the second occurring an approximate 0.8&nbsp;Ga.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|title = Oxygen fluctuations stalled life on Earth|year=2014|first=Jane|last=Qiu|url = http://www.nature.com/news/oxygen-fluctuations-stalled-life-on-earth-1.15529|journal = Nature|access-date = 2017-02-24 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1038/nature.2014.15529}}</ref> The intermediary period, during the Boring Billion, is thought have had low oxygen levels (with minor fluctuations), leading to widespread [[anoxic waters]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|title = The rise of oxygen in Earth's early ocean and atmosphere|year=2014|journal = Nature|pages = 307\u2013315|volume = 506|issue = 7488|doi = 10.1038/nature13068|pmid=24553238|first = Timothy W.|last = Lyons|first2 = Christopher T.|last2 = Reinhard|first3 = Noah J.|last3 = Planavsky|bibcode = 2014Natur.506..307L}}</ref>\n\nThe oceans may have been distinctly stratified, with surface water oxygenated,<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\"/> and deep water suboxic (less than 1 [[micromolar|\u03bcM]] oxygen),<ref name=DeBaar1988>{{cite journal|last=De Baar|first=H. J. W.|last2=German|first2=C. R.|last3=Elderfield|first3=H|last4=van Gaans|first4=P.|year=1988|title=Rare earth element distributions in anoxic waters of the Cariaco Trench|journal=Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta|volume=52|issue=5|pages=1203\u20131219|doi=10.1016/0016-7037(88)90275-X}}</ref> the latter possibly maintained by lower levels of [[hydrogen]] (H<sub>2</sub>) and H<sub>2</sub>S output by deep sea [[hydrothermal vent]]s which otherwise would have been chemically reduced by the oxygen.<ref name=Slack2009/> The [[decomposition]] of sinking organic matter would have also leeched oxygen from deep waters.<ref name=Johnston2009/><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe sudden drop in O<sub>2</sub> after the Great Oxygenation Event\u2014indicated by [[\u03b413C]] levels to have been loss of 10 to 20 times the current volume of atmospheric oxygen\u2014is known as the [[Lomagundi Excursion Event]], and is the most prominent [[Isotopes of carbon|carbon isotope]] event in Earth's history.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Large-scale fluctuations in Precambrian atmospheric and oceanic oxygen levels from the record of U in shales|journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date = 2013-05-01 |df=dmy-all |pages = 284\u2013293|volume = 369\u2013370|doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2013.03.031|first = C. A.|last = Partin|first2 = A.|last2 = Bekker|first3 = N. J.|last3 = Planavsky|first4 = C. T.|last4 = Scott|first5 = B. C.|last5 = Gill|first6 = C.|last6 = Li|first7 = V.|last7 = Podkovyrov|first8 = A.|last8 = Maslov|first9 = K. O.|last9 = Konhauser|bibcode=2013E&PSL.369..284P}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Oxygen overshoot and recovery during the early Paleoproterozoic|journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date = 2012-02-01 |df=dmy-all |pages = 295\u2013304|volume = 317\u2013318|doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2011.12.012|first = A.|last = Bekker|first2 = H. D.|last2 = Holland|bibcode=2012E&PSL.317..295B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Rise in seawater sulphate concentration associated with the Paleoproterozoic positive carbon isotope excursion: evidence from sulphate evaporites in the \u223c2.2\u20132.1 Gyr shallow-marine Lucknow Formation, South Africa|journal = Terra Nova|date = 2008-04-01 |df=dmy-all |issn = 1365-3121|pages = 108\u2013117|volume = 20|issue = 2|doi = 10.1111/j.1365-3121.2008.00795.x|language = en|first = S.|last = Schr\u00f6der|first2 = A.|last2 = Bekker|first3 = N. J.|last3 = Beukes|first4 = H.|last4 = Strauss|first5 = H. S.|last5 = Van Niekerk|bibcode = 2008TeNov..20..108S}}</ref> Oxygen levels may have been less than 0.1 to 2% of modern-day levels, which would have effectively stalled the evolution of complex life during the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Oxic conditions would have become dominant at the second oxygenation event causing the proliferation of [[Aerobic organism|aerobic]] activity over [[Anaerobic organism|anaerobic]],<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=Johnston2009/> but widespread suboxic and anoxic conditions likely lasted until about 0.55 Gya corresponding with [[Ediacaran biota]] and the [[Cambrian explosion]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=L. C.|last=Kah|first2=T. W.|last2=Lyons|first3=T. D.|last3=Frank|year=2004|title=Low marine sulphate and protracted oxygenation of the Proterozoic biosphere|journal=Nature|volume=438|issue=7010|pages=834\u2013838|doi=10.1038/nature02974|pmid=15483609|url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/geosciencefacpub/99}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=L. M.|last=Och|first2=G. A.|last2=Shields-Zhou|year=2012|title=The Neoproterozoic oxygenation event: Environmental perturbations and biogeochemical cycling|journal=Earth-Science Reviews|volume=110|issue=1\u20134|pages=26\u201357|doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2011.09.004}}</ref>\n\n===Sulfur===\n[[File:How oceans become euxinic.png|thumb|upright=2|Diagram of how [[euxinic]] conditions form]]\nIn 1998, geologist [[Donald Canfield]] proposed what is now known as the [[Canfield ocean]] hypothesis. Canfield claimed that increasing levels of oxygen in the atmosphere at the Great Oxygenation Event would have reacted with and oxidized continental [[iron pyrite]] (FeS<sub>2</sub>) deposits, with [[sulfate]] (SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup>) as a byproduct, which was transported into the sea. [[Sulfate-reducing microorganisms]] converted this to [[hydrogen sulfide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S), dividing the ocean into a somewhat oxic surface layer, and a sulfidic layer beneath, with [[anoxygenic photosynthesis|anoxygenic]] bacteria living at the border, metabolizing the H<sub>2</sub>S and creating sulfur as a waste product. This created widespread [[euxinic]] conditions in middle-waters, an anoxic state with a high sulfur concentration, which was maintained by the bacteria.<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Lyons| first = Timothy W.| last2 = Reinhard| first2 = Christopher T.| year=2009 |df=dmy-all| title = An early productive ocean unfit for aerobics| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume = 106| issue = 43\n |pages = 18045\u201318046| doi = 10.1073/pnas.0910345106| issn = 0027-8424| pmc = 2775325| pmid = 19846788| bibcode = 2009PNAS..10618045L}}</ref><ref name=Canfield1998>{{Cite journal| last = Canfield| first = D. E.\n| year=1998|df=dmy-all| title = A new model for Proterozoic ocean chemistry| journal = Nature| volume = 396| issue = 6710| pages = 450\u2013453| doi = 10.1038/24839| issn = 0028-0836| bibcode = 1998Natur.396..450C}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Biodiversity and Earth History|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ct29BwAAQBAJ|publisher = Springer|date = 2015-03-31|isbn = 9783662463949|language = en|first = Jens|last = Boenigk|first2 = Sabina|last2 = Wodniok|first3 = Edvard|last3 = Gl\u00fccksman}}</ref><ref name=Johnston2009>{{Cite journal|title = Anoxygenic photosynthesis modulated Proterozoic oxygen and sustained Earth's middle age|last = Johnston|first = D. T. |year=2009 |journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|doi = 10.1073/pnas.0909248106 |pmid = 19805080|pmc = 2753640|volume=106|issue = 40|pages=16925\u201316929|bibcode =2009PNAS..10616925J}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Large|first2=J. A.|last2=Halpin|first3=L. V.|last3=Danyushevsky|year=2014|title=Trace element content of sedimentary pyrite as a new proxy for deep-time ocean\u2013atmosphere evolution|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=389|pages=209\u2013220|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2013.12.020}}</ref>\n\n===Iron===\nAmong rocks dating to the Boring Billion, there is a conspicuous lack of [[banded iron formation]]s, which form from iron in the upper water column reacting with oxygen and precipitating out of the water, with the iron deriving from the deep sea. They seemingly cease around the world after 1.85 Ga. Canfield said that oceanic SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup> [[redox|reduced]] all the iron in the anoxic deep sea, as opposed to oxygen as previously supposed.<ref name=Canfield1998/> Iron could have been metabolized by anoxygenic bacteria.<ref name=Canfield2018/> It has also been proposed that the 1.85 Ga [[Sudbury Basin|Sudbury meteor impact]] mixed the previously stratified Canfield ocean via tsunamis, interaction between vaporized seawater and the oxygenated atmosphere, oceanic [[cavitation]], and massive runoff of destroyed [[continental margin]]s into the sea. Resultant suboxic deep waters (due to oxygenated surface water mixing with previously anoxic deep water) would have oxidized deep-water iron, preventing it from being transported and deposited on continental margins.<ref name=Slack2009>{{cite journal|first=J. F.|last=Slack|first2=W. F.|last2=Cannon|year=2009|title=Extraterrestrial demise of banded iron formations 1.85 billion years ago|journal=Geology|volume=37|issue=11|pages=1011\u20131014|doi=10.1130/G30259A.1}}</ref>\n\nNonetheless, iron-rich (ferrous) waters did exist, such as the 1.4 Ga [[Xiamaling Formation]] of Northern China, which perhaps was fed by deep water hydrothermal vents. Ferrous conditions also indicate anoxic bottom water in this area, as oxic conditions would have oxidized all the iron.<ref name=Canfield2018>{{cite journal|first=D. E.|last=Canfield|authorlink=Donald Canfield|first2=S.|last2=Zhang|first3=H.|last3=Wang|first4=X.|last4=Wang|first5=W.|last5=Zhao|first6=J.|last6=Su|first7=C. J.|last7=Bjerrum|first8=E. R.|last8=Haxen|first9=E. U.|last9=Hammarlund|year=2018|title=A Mesoproterozoic iron formation|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=17|pages=3895\u20133904|doi=10.1073/pnas.1720529115|pmid=29632173|pmc=5924912}}</ref>\n\n==Lifeforms==\nLow nutrient abundance may have caused increased [[symbiosis|photosymbiosis]]\u2014where one organism is capable of photosynthesis and the other metabolizes the waste product\u2014among [[prokaryote]]s ([[bacteria]] and [[archaea]]), and the emergence of [[eukaryote]]s. Bacteria, Archaea, and Eukaryota are the three [[domain (biology)|domains]], the highest taxonomic ranking. Eukaryotes are distinguished from prokaryotes by a [[cell nucleus|nucleus]] and membrane-bound organelles, and all multicellular organisms are eukaryotes.<ref name=Brasier1998>{{cite journal|first=M. D.|last=Brasier|first2=J. F.|last2=Lindsay|year=1998|title=A billion years of environmental stability and the emergence of eukaryotes: new data from northern Australia|journal=Geology|volume=26|issue=6|pages=555\u2013558|doi=10.1130/0091-7613(1998)026<0555:ABYOES>2.3.CO;2|pmid=11541449}}</ref>\n\n===Prokaryotes===\n[[File:Stromatolites, Belt Supergroup, Glacier National Park.jpg|thumb|1.44 Ga [[stromatolite]] from [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]], Montana]]\nProkaryotes were the dominant lifeforms throughout the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=Gueneli/><ref name=Canfield1998/> Anoxygenic cyanobacteria are thought to have been the dominant photosynthesizers, metabolizing the abundant H<sub>2</sub>S in the oceans. However, in iron-rich waters, cyanobacteria may have suffered from [[iron poisoning]], especially in offshore waters were iron-rich deep water mixed with surface waters, and were outcompeted by other bacteria which could metabolize both iron and H<sub>2</sub>S. However, iron poisoning could have been abated by [[silica]]-rich waters or [[biomineralization]] of iron within the cell.<ref name=Javaux2018>{{cite journal|first=E. J.|last=Javaux|first2=K.|last2=Lepot|year=2018|title=The Paleoproterozoic fossil record: Implications for the evolution of the biosphere during Earth's middle-age|journal=Earth-Science Reviews|volume=176|pages=68\u201386|doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2017.10.001}}</ref>\n\n[[Microfossil]]s indicate the presence of cyanobacteria, [[green sulfur bacteria|green]] and [[purple sulfur bacteria|purple]] sulfur bacteria, methane-producing archaea or bacteria, sulfate-metabolizing bacteria, [[methanotroph|methane-metabolizing]] archaea or bacteria, iron-metabolizing bacteria, [[denitrifying bacteria|nitrogen-metabolizing]] bacteria, and anoxygenic photosynthetic bacteria.<ref name=Javaux2018/>\n\n===Eukaryotes===\nEukaryotes may have arisen around the beginning of the Boring Billion,<ref name=Mukherjee2018/> coinciding with the accretion of Columbia, which could have somehow increased oceanic oxygen levels.<ref name=Brooke2014/> However, multicellular eukaryotes possibly already evolved by this time, with the earliest claimed fossil evidence dating to the Great Oxygenation Event with jellyfish-like [[Francevillian biota]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=A.|last=El Albani|first2=S.|last2=Bengtson|first3=D. E.|last3=Canfield|authorlink3=Donald Canfield|first4=A.|last4=Bekkler|year=2010|title=Large colonial organisms with coordinated growth in oxygenated environments 2.1 Gyr ago|journal=Nature|volume=466|issue=7302|pages=100\u2013104|doi=10.1038/nature09166|pmid=20596019|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/44902514}}</ref> Following this, eukaryotic evolution was rather slow,<ref name=\":10\" /> possibly due to the euxinic conditions of the Canfield ocean and a lack of key nutrients and metals<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=Mukherjee2018/> which prevented large, complex life with high energy requirements from evolving.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|title = Low Mid-Proterozoic atmospheric oxygen levels and the delayed rise of animals|journal = Science|date = 2014-10-31 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0036-8075|pmid = 25359975|pages = 635\u2013638|volume = 346|issue = 6209|doi = 10.1126/science.1258410|language = en|first = Noah J.|last = Planavsky|first2 = Christopher T.|last2 = Reinhard|first3 = Xiangli|last3 = Wang|first4 = Danielle|last4 = Thomson|first5 = Peter|last5 = McGoldrick|first6 = Robert H.|last6 = Rainbird|first7 = Thomas|last7 = Johnson|first8 = Woodward W.|last8 = Fischer|first9 = Timothy W.|last9 = Lyons|bibcode = 2014Sci...346..635P|url = https://authors.library.caltech.edu/50325/13/Planavsky.SM.pdf}}</ref> Euxinic conditions would have also decreased the solubility of iron<ref name=Canfield1998/> and [[molybdenum]],<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Reinhard| first = C. T.| last2 = Planavsky| first2 = N. J.| last3 = Robbins| first3 = L. J.| last4 = Partin| first4 = C. A.| last5 = Gill| first5 = B. C.| last6 = Lalonde| first6 = S. V.| last7 = Bekker| first7 = A.| last8 = Konhauser| first8 = K. O.| last9 = Lyons| first9 = T. W.| year=2013|df=dmy-all | title = Proterozoic ocean redox and biogeochemical stasis| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume = 110| issue = 14| pages = 5357\u20135362| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1208622110| issn = 0027-8424| pmc = 3619314| pmid = 23515332| bibcode = 2013PNAS..110.5357R}}</ref> essential metals in [[nitrogen fixation]]. A lack of dissolved nitrogen would have favored prokaryotes over eukaryotes, as the former can metabolize gaseous nitrogen.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal| last = Anbar| first = A. D.| year=2002 |df=dmy-all | title = Proterozoic ocean chemistry and evolution: a bioinorganic bridge| journal = Science| volume = 297| issue = 5584| pages = 1137\u20131142| doi = 10.1126/science.1069651| pmid = 12183619| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1137A}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ramathallus lobatus.png|thumb|left|upright|1.6 Ga ''[[Ramathallus]]'' fossil, the earliest known [[red alga]]<ref name=Bengtson2017/>]]\nNonetheless, the diversification of [[crown group]] eukaryotic macroorganisms seems to have started about 1.6\u20131 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=S.|last=Bengtson|first2=V.|last2=Belivanova|first3=B.|last3=Rasmussen|first4=M.|last4=Whitehouse|year=2009|title=The controversial \"Cambrian\" fossils of the Vindhyan are real but more than a billion years older|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=106|issue=19|pages=7729\u20137734|doi=10.1073/pnas.0812460106|pmid=19416859|pmc=2683128}}</ref> seemingly coinciding with an increase in key nutrient concentrations.<ref name=Mukherjee2018/> According to phylogenetic analysis, plants diverged from animals and fungi about 1.6 Gya; animals and fungi about 1.5 Gya; [[Bilateria]]ns and [[cnidaria]]ns (animals respectively with and without [[bilateral symmetry]]) about 1.3 Gya; [[sponge]]s 1.35 Gya;<ref name=Hedges2004/> and [[Ascomycota]] and [[Basidiomycota]] (the two divisions of the fungus [[subkingdom]] [[Dikarya]]) 0.97 Gya.<ref name=Hedges2004/> The earliest known [[red algae]] mats date to 1.6 Gya.<ref name=Bengtson2017>{{cite journal|first=S.|last=Bengtson|first2=T.|last2=Sallstedt|first3=V.|last3=Belivanova|first4=M.|last4=Whitehouse|year=2017|title=Three-dimensional preservation of cellular and subcellular structures suggests 1.6 billion-year-old crown-group red algae|journal=PLOS Biology|volume=15|issue=3|page=e2000735|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.2000735|pmc=5349422|pmid=28291791}}</ref> The earliest known fungus dates to 1.01\u20130.89 Gya from Northern Canada.<ref name=Loron2019>{{cite journal|first=C. C.|last=Loron|first2=C.|last2=Fran\u00e7ois|first3=R. H.|last3=Rainbird|first4=E. C.|last4=Turner|first5=S.|last5=Borensztajn|first6=E. J.|last6=Javaux|year=2019|title=Early fungi from the Proterozoic era in Arctic Canada|journal=Nature|volume=70|pages=232\u2013235|issue=7760|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333301933|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1217-0|pmid=31118507}}</ref> Multicellular eukaryotes had probably evolved about 2\u20131.4 Gya, thought to be the descendants of colonial unicellular aggregates.<ref>{{cite book|first=G. M.|last=Cooper|year=2000|chapter=The Origin and Evolution of Cells|title=The Cell: A Molecular Approach|edition=2nd|publisher=Sinauer Associates|chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9841/}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Niklas|first=K. J.|year=2014|title=The evolutionary-developmental origins of multicellularity|journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=101|issue=1|pages=6\u201325|doi=10.3732/ajb.1300314|pmid=24363320}}</ref> Likewise, early multicellular eukaryotes likely mainly aggregated into [[stromatolite]] mats.<ref name=Brooke2014>{{cite book|first=J. L.|last=Brooke|year=2014|title=Climate Change and the Course of Global History: A Rough Journey|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=40\u201342|isbn=978-0-521-87164-8}}</ref>\n\nThe 1.2 Ga red alga ''[[Bangiomorpha]]'' is the earliest known sexually reproducing and [[meiosis|meiotic]] lifeform,<ref>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285932986 |chapter=DNA Repair as the Primary Adaptive Function of Sex in Bacteria and Eukaryotes |pages=1\u201349 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202307/https://www.novapublishers.com/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=31918# |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead|last1=Bernstein|first1=H.|last2=Bernstein|first2=C.|last3=Michod|first3=R. E.|editor1-last=Kimura| editor1-first=S.|editor2-last=Shimizu|editor2-first=S.|publisher=Nova Biomedical|isbn=978-1-62100-756-2|title=DNA Repair: New Research|date=2012}}</ref> and, based on this, these adaptations evolved 2\u20131.4 Gya.<ref name=Mukherjee2018>{{cite journal|first=I.|last=Mukherjee|first2=R. R.|last2=Large|first3=R.|last3=Corkrey|first4=L. V.|last4=Danyushevsky|year=2018|title=The Boring Billion, a slingshot for Complex Life on Earth|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=4432|pages=4432|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-22695-x|pmid=29535324|pmc=5849639}}</ref> However, these may have evolved well before the last common ancestor of eukaryotes given that meiosis is performed using the same proteins in all eukaryotes, perhaps stretching to as far back as the hypothesized [[RNA world]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Egel|first2=D.|last2=Penny|year=2007|title=On the Origin of Meiosis in Eukaryotic Evolution: Coevolution of Meiosis and Mitosis from Feeble Beginnings|journal=Genome Dynamics and Stability|volume=3|issue=249\u2013288|pages=249\u2013288|doi=10.1007/7050_2007_036|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226518084|isbn=978-3-540-68983-6}}</ref>\n\nCell [[organelle]]s probably originated from free-living [[cyanobacteria]] ([[symbiogenesis]])<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{cite journal |title=Endosymbiotic gene transfer: organelle genomes forge eukaryotic chromosomes|journal=Nature Reviews Genetics|year=2004|pages=123\u2013135|volume=5|issue=2|doi=10.1038/nrg1271|first=J. N.|last=Timmis|first2=Michael A.|last2=Ayliffe|first3=C. Y.|last3=Huang|first4=W.|last4=Martin|pmid=14735123}}</ref><ref name=Mukherjee2018/> possibly after the evolution of [[phagocytosis]] (engulfing other cells) with the removal of the rigid [[cell wall]] which was only necessary for asexual reproduction.<ref name=\":10\" /> [[Mitochondria]] had already evolved in the Great Oxygenation Event, but [[plastid]]s used in plants for namely [[photosynthesis]] are thought to have appeared about 1.6\u20131.5 Gya.<ref name=Hedges2004>{{cite journal|first=S. B.|last=Hedges|first2=J. E.|last2=Blair|first3=M. L.|last3=Venturi|first4=J. L.|last4=Shoe|year=2004|title=A molecular timescale of eukaryote evolution and the rise of complex multicellular life|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=4|issue=2|pages=2|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-4-2|pmc=341452|pmid=15005799}}</ref> [[Histone]]s likely appeared during the Boring Billion to help organize and package the increasing amount of DNA in eukaryotic cells into [[nucleosome]]s.<ref name=\":10\" /> [[Hydrogenosome]]s used in anaerobic activity may have originated in this time from an archaeon.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|title = Energy metabolism among eukaryotic anaerobes in light of Proterozoic ocean chemistry|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|date = 2008-08-27 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 2606767|pmid = 18468979|pages = 2717\u20132729|volume = 363|issue = 1504|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2008.0031|language = en|first = Marek|last = Mentel|first2 = William|last2 = Martin}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal| last = Martin| first = W.| last2 = M\u00fcller| first2 = M.| year=1998 |df=dmy-all| title = The hydrogen hypothesis for the first eukaryote| journal = Nature| volume = 392| issue = 6671| pages = 37\u201341| doi = 10.1038/32096| issn = 0028-0836| pmid=9510246| bibcode = 1998Natur.392...37M}}</ref>\n\nGiven the evolutionary landmarks achieved by eukaryotes, this time period could be considered an important precursor to the Cambrian explosion about 0.54 Gya, and the evolution of relatively large, complex life.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Ecology===\nDue to the marginalization of large food particles, such as algae, in favor of cyanobacteria and prokaryotes which do not transmit as much energy to higher [[trophic level]]s, a complex [[food web]] likely did not form, and large lifeforms with high energy demands could not evolve. Such a food web probably only sustained a small number of [[protist]]s as, in a sense, [[apex predator]]s.<ref name=Gueneli>{{cite journal|first=N.|last=Gueneli|first2=A. M.|last2=McKenna|first3=N.|last3=Ohkouchi|first4=C. J.|last4=Boreham|first5=J.|last5=Beghin|first6=E. J.|last6=Javaux|first7=J. J.|last7=Brocks|year=2018|title=1.1-billion-year-old porphyrins establish a marine ecosystem dominated by bacterial primary producers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=30|pages=6978\u20136986|doi=10.1073/pnas.1803866115|pmid=29987033|pmc=6064987}}</ref>\n\nThe presumably oxygenic photosynthetic eukaryotic [[acritarch]]s, perhaps a type of [[microalga]], inhabited the Mesoproterozoic surface waters.<ref>{{cite journal|first=M.|last=Moczydlowska|first2=E.|last2=Landing|first3=W.|last3=Zang|first4=T.|last4=Palacios|year=2011|title=Proterozoic phytoplankton and timing of Chlorophyte algae origins|journal=Palaeontology|volume=54|issue=4|pages=721\u2013733|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4983.2011.01054.x}}</ref> Their population may have been largely limited by nutrient availability rather than predation because species have been reported to have survived for hundreds of millions of years, but after 1 Gya, species duration dropped to about 100 Ma, perhaps due to increased herbivory by early protists. This is consistent with species survival dropping to 10 Ma just after the Cambrian explosion and the expansion of herbivorous animals.<ref>{{cite journal|first=S. M.|last=Stanley|year=2008|title=Predation defeats competition on the seafloor|journal=Paleobiology|volume=31|issue=1|page=12<!--only citing this page-->|doi=10.1666/07026.1}}</ref>\n\n===Life on land===\nSome of the earliest evidence of the prokaryotic colonization of land dates to before 3 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Homann|first=M.|display-authors=et al.|year=2018|title=Microbial life and biogeochemical cycling on land 3,220 million years ago|journal=Nature Geoscience|volume=11|issue=9|pages=665\u2013671|doi=10.1038/s41561-018-0190-9}}</ref> possibly as early as 3.5 Gya.<ref>{{cite journal|first=R. J.|last=Baumgartner|first2=M. J.|last2=van Kranendonk|display-authors=et al.|title=Nano\u2212porous pyrite and organic matter in 3.5-billion-year-old stromatolites record primordial life|journal=Geology|volume=47|issue=11|pages=1039\u20131043|year=2019|doi=10.1130/G46365.1}}</ref> During the Boring Billion, land may have been inhabited mainly by cyanobacterial mats.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Watanabe |first=Yumiko|last2=Martini |first2=Jacques E. J. |last3=Ohmoto |first3=Hiroshi |date=2000-11-30 |df=dmy-all |title=Geochemical evidence for terrestrial ecosystems 2.6 billion years ago |journal=Nature|volume=408 |issue=6812 |pages=574\u2013578 |doi=10.1038/35046052 |issn=0028-0836 |pmid=11117742 |bibcode=2000Natur.408..574W}}</ref><ref name=Horodyski1994>{{Cite journal |last=Horodyski |first=R. J. |last2=Knauth |first2=L. P. |year=1994 |df=dmy-all |title=Life on land in the precambrian |journal=Science |volume=263 |issue=5146 |pages=494\u2013498 |doi=10.1126/science.263.5146.494 |issn=0036-8075 |pmid=17754880 |bibcode=1994Sci...263..494H}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Retallack |first=Gregory J. |last2=Mindszenty |first2=Andrea |date=1994-04-01 |df=dmy-all |title=Well preserved late Precambrian Paleosols from Northwest Scotland |url=http://jsedres.geoscienceworld.org/content/64/2a/264 |journal=Journal of Sedimentary Research |language=en |volume=64 |issue=2a |pages=264\u2013281 |doi=10.1306/D4267D7A-2B26-11D7-8648000102C1865D |issn=1527-1404}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Horodyski| first = R. J.| last2 = Knauth| first2 = L. P.| year=1994 |df=dmy-all| title = Life on land in the precambrian| journal = Science| volume = 263| issue = 5146| pages = 494\u2013498| doi = 10.1126/science.263.5146.494| issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 17754880| bibcode = 1994Sci...263..494H}}</ref> Dust would have supplied an abundance of nutrients and a means of dispersal for surface-dwelling microbes, though microbial communities could have also formed in caves and freshwater lakes and rivers.<ref name=Campesi2013/><ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://risweb.st-andrews.ac.uk/portal/da/researchoutput/life-on-land-in-the-proterozoic-evidence-from-the-torridonian-rocks-of-northwest-scotland(b8c702c9-ba95-4ac8-b78c-84293f17881d).html |title=Life on land in the Proterozoic: Evidence from the Torridonian rocks of northwest Scotland |volume=30 |issue=9 |pages=811 |journal=Geology |year=2002 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(2002)030<0811:LOLITP>2.0.CO;2 |first=Anthony Robert |last=Prave |access-date=2016-03-05 |df=dmy-all |bibcode=2002Geo....30..811P}}</ref> By 1.2 Gya, microbial communities may have been abundant enough to have affected weathering, [[erosion]], sedimentation, and various geochemical cycles,<ref name=Horodyski1994/> and expansive microbial mats could indicate [[biological soil crust]] was abundant.<ref name=Campesi2013>{{cite journal|first=H.|last=Beraldi-Campesi|year=2013|title=Early life on land and the first terrestrial ecosystems|journal=Ecological Processes|volume=2|issue=1|pages=1\u201317|doi=10.1186/2192-1709-2-1}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest terrestrial eukaryotes may have been lichen fungi about 1.3 Ga,<ref name=Heckman2001>{{cite journal|first=D. S.|last=Heckman|first2=D. M.|last2=Geiser|first3=B. R.|last3=Eidell|first4=R. L.|last4=Stauffer|first5=N. L.|last5=Kardos|first6=S. B.|last6=Hedges|year=2001|title=Molecular Evidence for the Early Colonization of Land by Fungi and Plants|journal=Science|volume=293|issue=5532|pages=494\u2013498|doi=10.1126/science.263.5146.494|pmid=17754880}}</ref> which grazed on the microbial mats.<ref name=Campesi2013/> Abundant eukaryotic microfossils from the freshwater Scottish [[Torridon Group]] seems to indicate eukaryotic dominance in non-marine habitats by 1 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=P. K.|last=Strother|first2=L.|last2=Battison|first3=M. D.|last3=Brasier|authorlink3=Martin Brasier|first4=C. H.|last4=Wellman|year=2011|title=Earth's earliest non-marine eukaryotes|journal=Nature|volume=473|issue=7348|pages=505\u2013509|doi=10.1038/nature09943|pmid=21490597|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/51048998}}</ref> probably due to increased nutrient availability in areas closer to the continents and continental runoff.<ref name=Parnell2015/> These lichen may have later facilitated plant colonization 0.75 Gya in some manner.<ref name=Heckman2001/> A massive increase in terrestrial photosynthetic biomass seems to have occurred about 0.85 Gya, indicated by a flux in terrestrially-sourced carbon, which may have increased oxygen levels enough to support an expansion of multicellular eukaryotes.<ref>{{cite journal|first=L. P.|last=Knauth|year=2009|title=The late Precambrian greening of the Earth|journal=Nature|volume=460|issue=7256|pages=728\u2013732|doi=10.1038/nature08213|pmid=19587681}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Precambrian}}\n*{{annotated link|Ediacaran biota}}\n*{{annotated link|Francevillian biota}}\n*{{annotated link|Snowball Earth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|first=M.|last=Brasier|year=2012|title=Secret Chambers: The Inside Story of Cells and Complex Life|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-964400-1|ref={{harvid|Brasier|2012}}}}\n\n[[Category:Proterozoic]]\n[[Category:Geological history of Earth]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Between 1.8 and 0.8 billion years ago}}\n{{Life timeline}}\nThe '''Boring Billion''', otherwise known as the '''Barren Billion''', the '''Dullest Time in Earth's History''', and '''Earth's Middle Ages''', is the time period between 1.8 and 0.8 billion years ago (Gya) spanning the middle [[Proterozoic]] [[eon (geology)|eon]], characterized by more or less [[tectonic]] stability, climatic stasis, and stalled biological evolution. It is bordered by two different oxygenation and glacial events, but the Boring Billion itself had very low oxygen levels and no evidence of glaciation.\n\nThe oceans may have been oxygen- and nutrient-poor and sulfidic ([[euxinia]]), populated by mainly [[anoxygenic photosynthesis|anoxygenic]] [[cyanobacteria]], a type of photosynthetic bacteria which uses [[hydrogen sulfide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S) instead of water and produces [[sulfur]] instead of oxygen. This is known as a [[Canfield ocean]]. Such composition may have caused the oceans to be black- and milky-turquoise instead of blue.\n\nDespite such adverse conditions, [[eukaryote]]s may have evolved around the beginning of the Boring Billion, and adopted several novel adaptations, such as various [[organelle]]s and possibly [[evolution of sexual reproduction|sexual reproduction]], and diversified into [[plant]]s, [[animal]]s, and [[fungi]]. Such advances may have been important precursors to the evolution of large, complex life later in the [[Cambrian explosion]]. However, [[prokaryotic]] cyanobacteria were the dominant lifeforms during this time, and likely supported an energy-poor [[food-web]] with a small number of [[protist]]s at the [[apex predator|apex level]]. The land was likely inhabited by prokaryotic cyanobacteria and eukaryotic proto-[[lichen]]s, the latter more successful here probably due to the greater availability of nutrients than offshore ocean waters.\n\n==Description==\nIn 1995, geologists [[Roger Buick]], [[Davis Des Marais]], and [[Andrew Knoll]] reviewed the apparent lack of major biological, geological, and climatic events during the [[Mesoproterozoic]] [[era]] 1.6 to 1 billion years ago (Gya), and, thus, described it as \"the dullest time in Earth's history\".<ref name=Buick1995>{{Cite journal|title = Stable isotopic compositions of carbonates from the Mesoproterozoic Bangemall group, northwestern Australia|journal = Chemical Geology|year=1995|pages = 153\u2013171|volume = 123|issue = 1\u20134|doi = 10.1016/0009-2541(95)00049-R|pmid = 11540130|first = R.|last = Buick|first2 = D. J.|last2 = Des Marais|first3 = A. H.|last3 = Knoll|authorlink3=Andrew Knoll|bibcode = 1995ChGeo.123..153B}}</ref> The term \"Boring Billion\" was coined by paleontologist [[Martin Brasier]] to refer to the time between about 2 and 1 Gya, which was characterized by geochemical stasis and glacial stagnation.{{sfn|Brasier|2012|loc=p. 211}} In 2013, geochemist [[Grant Young (geochemist)|Grant Young]] used the term \"Barren Billion\" to refer to a period of apparent glacial stagnation and lack of carbon isotope excursions from 1.8 to 0.8 Gya.<ref name=:4/> In 2014, geologists [[Peter Cawood]] and [[Chris Hawkesworth]] called the time between 1.7 and 0.75 Gya \"Earth's Middle Ages\" due to a lack of evidence of tectonic movement.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nThe Boring Billion is now largely cited as spanning about 1.8 to 0.8 Gya, contained within the [[Proterozoic]] [[eon (geology)|eon]], mainly the Mesoproterozoic. The Boring Billion is characterized by geological, climatic, and by-and-large evolutionary stasis, with low nutrient abundance.<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=Mukherjee2018/><ref name=Holland2006/><ref name=Peng2019/>\n\nIn the time leading up to the Boring Billion, Earth experienced the [[Great Oxygenation Event]] due to the evolution of [[oxygenic photosynthesis|oxygenic photosynthetic]] [[cyanobacteria]], and the resultant [[Huronian glaciation]] ([[Snowball Earth]]), formation of the [[UV]]-blocking [[ozone layer]], and oxidation of several metals.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book| year = 2011| last = Lenton| first = T.| last2 = Watson| first2 = A.| pages = 242\u2013261| doi = 10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199587049.003.0013|title = Revolutions that made the Earth|isbn = 9780199587049}}</ref> Boring Billion oxygen levels dramatically dropped.<ref name=\":10\" /> It was ended by the breakup of the supercontinent [[Rodinia]], a second oxygenation event, and another Snowball Earth in the [[Cryogenian]] period.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|title = Earth's middle age|journal = Geology|date = 2014-06-01|issn = 0091-7613|pages = 503\u2013506|volume = 42|issue = 6|doi = 10.1130/G35402.1|language = en|first = Peter A.|last = Cawood|first2 = Chris J.|last2 = Hawkesworth|bibcode = 2014Geo....42..503C}}</ref><ref name=Brooke2014/>\n\n== Tectonic stasis ==\n{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=Paleoglobe NO 1590 mya-vector-colors.svg|image2=Rodinia reconstruction.jpg|footer=Reconstruction of [[Columbia (supercontinent)|Columbia]] (above, 1.6 Gya) and [[Rodinia]] after break-up (below, 0.75 Gya)}}\nThe evolution of Earth's [[biosphere]], atmosphere, and [[hydrosphere]] has long been linked to the [[supercontinent cycle]], where the continents aggregate and then drift apart. The Boring Billion saw the evolution of two supercontinents: [[Columbia (supercontinent)|Columbia]] (or Nuna) and [[Rodinia]].<ref name=Evans2013/>\n\nThe supercontinent Columbia formed between 2.0 and 1.7&nbsp;Ga and remained intact until at least 1.3&nbsp;Ga. Geological and [[Paleomagnetism|paleomagnetic]] evidence suggest that Columbia underwent only minor changes to form the supercontinent Rodinia from 1.1 to 0.9&nbsp;Ga. [[Palaeogeography|Paleogeographic]] reconstructions suggest that the supercontinent assemblage was located in [[equator]]ial and [[Temperate climate|temperate]] climate zones, and there is little or no evidence for continental fragments in [[polar region]]s.<ref name=Evans2013>{{Cite journal|title = Reconstructing pre-Pangean supercontinents|year=2013|journal = Geological Society of America Bulletin|pages = 1735\u20131751|volume = 125|issue = 11\u201312|doi = 10.1130/b30950.1|first = D. A. D.|last = Evans|bibcode = 2013GSAB..125.1735E}}</ref>\n\nDue to the lack of evidence of sediment build-up (on passive margins) which would occur as a result of [[rift]]ing,<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Passive margins through earth history|journal = Earth-Science Reviews|date = 2008-12-01|pages = 1\u201326|volume = 91|issue = 1\u20134|doi = 10.1016/j.earscirev.2008.08.001|first = Dwight C.|last = Bradley|bibcode = 2008ESRv...91....1B|url = https://zenodo.org/record/1258907}}</ref> the supercontinent probably did not break up, and rather was simply an assemblage of juxtaposed proto-continents and [[craton]]s. There is no evidence of rifting until the formation of Rodinia, 1.25 Gya in North Laurentia, and 1 Gya in East [[Baltica]] and South [[Siberia]].<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\" /> However, breakup did not occur until 0.75 Gya, marking the end of the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":1\" /> This tectonic stasis may have been related in ocean and atmospheric chemistry.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = The boring billion? \u2013 Lid tectonics, continental growth and environmental change associated with the Columbia supercontinent|journal = Geoscience Frontiers|year=2013 |df=dmy-all |pages = 681\u2013691|volume = 4|series = Thematic Section: Antarctica \u2013 A window to the far off land|issue = 6|doi = 10.1016/j.gsf.2013.05.004|first = N. M. W.|last = Roberts}}</ref><ref name=Holland2006>{{Cite journal|title = The oxygenation of the atmosphere and oceans|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|date = 2006-06-29|issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 1578726|pmid = 16754606|pages = 903\u2013915|volume = 361|issue = 1470|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2006.1838|language = en|first = Heinrich D.|last = Holland}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIt is possible the [[asthenosphere]]\u2014the molten layer of Earth's [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] that tectonic plates essentially float and move around upon\u2014was too hot to sustain modern plate tectonics at this time. Instead of vigorous plate recycling at [[Subduction|subduction zones]], plates were linked together for billions of years until the mantle cooled off enough. The onset of this component of plate tectonics may have been aided by the cooling and thickening of the [[Crust (geology)|crust]] that, once initiated, caused plate subduction to be anomalously strong, occurring at the end of the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNonetheless, major [[magma]]tic events still occurred, namely the formation (via [[magma plume]]) of the {{cvt|220,000|km2|mi2|adj=on}} central Australian [[Musgrave Province]] from 1.22 to 1.12 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=W.|last=Gorczyk|first2=H.|last2=Smithies|first3=F.|last3=Korhonen|first4=H.|last4=Howard|first5=R. Q.|last5=de Gromard|year=2015|title=Ultra-hot Mesoproterozoic evolution of intracontinental central Australia|journal=Geoscience Frontiers|volume=6|issue=1|pages=23\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.gsf.2014.03.001}}</ref> and the {{cvt|2,700,000|km2|mi2}} Canadian [[Mackenzie Large Igneous Province]] 1.27 Gya;<ref>{{cite journal|first=S. E.|last=Bryan|first2=L.|last2=Ferrari|year=2013|title=Large igneous provinces and silicic large igneous provinces: Progress in our understanding over the last 25 years|journal=GSA Bulletin|volume=125|issue=7\u20138|page=1055<!--only citing this page-->|doi=10.1130/B30820.1}}</ref> and plate tectonics were still active enough to build mountains, with several [[orogenies]] known from the time, such as the [[Grenville orogeny]].<ref name=\"one\">{{Cite book |last=Tollo |first=R. P. |first2=L.|last2=Corriveau |first3=J.|last3=McLelland |first4=M. J.|last4=Bartholomew  |year=2004 |chapter=Proterozoic tectonic evolution of the Grenville orogen in North America: An introduction |editor1-last=Tollo |editor1-first=R. P. |editor2-first=L. |editor2-last=Corriveau |editor3-first=J. |editor3-last=McLelland |editor4-first=M. J. |editor4-last=Bartholomew |title=Proterozoic tectonic evolution of the Grenville orogen in North America |series=Geological Society of America Memoir |volume=197 |pages=1\u201318 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uT4HISRCon8C&pg=PA1&q  |isbn=978-0-8137-1197-3 }}</ref>\n\n== Climatic stability ==\n[[File:Mesoproterozoic temperature.jpg|thumb|300px|Graph showing average temperatures during the Mesoproterozoic. Blue line uses CO<sub>2</sub> concentration 5 times modern day, red line 10 times, and red dot shows average temperature range at the tropics]]\nThere is little evidence of significant climatic variability during this time period.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|title = Precambrian supercontinents, glaciations, atmospheric oxygenation, metazoan evolution and an impact that may have changed the second half of Earth history|journal = Geoscience Frontiers|year=2013|pages = 247\u2013261|volume = 4|issue = 3|doi = 10.1016/j.gsf.2012.07.003|first = Grant M.|last = Young}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title = A billion years of environmental stability and the emergence of eukaryotes: New data from northern Australia |last = Brasier |first = M.D. |year= 1998 |journal = Geology|doi =10.1130/0091-7613(1998)026<0555:ABYOES>2.3.CO;2 |pmid = 11541449 |volume=26 |issue = 6|pages = 555\u2013558 |bibcode = 1998Geo....26..555B }}</ref>  Climate was likely not primarily dictated by solar luminosity, because, if it were, all water on the planet would have been locked up in ice\u2014which was not the case according to the fossil record\u2014<ref name=Veizer2005/> because the sun was 5\u201318% less intense than today ([[faint young Sun paradox]]).<ref name=Fiorella2017>{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Fiorella|first2=N.|last2=Sheldon|year=2017|title=Equable end Mesoproterozoic climate in the absence of high CO2|journal=Geology|volume=45|issue=3|pages=231\u2013234|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/311885954|doi=10.1130/G38682.1}}</ref> In fact, the Boring Billion is unique in a sense that it seems to lack any evidence of significant periods of prolonged glaciations, which can be observed in regular periodicity in other parts of Earth's geologic history.<ref name=Veizer2005/> High CO<sub>2</sub> could not have been a main driver because levels would have needed to be 30 to 100 times greater than pre-[[Industrial Revolution|industrial]] levels<ref name=Fiorella2017/> and produced substantial [[ocean acidification]]<ref name=Veizer2005/> to prevent ice formation, which also did not occur. Mesoproterozoic CO<sub>2</sub> levels may have been comparable to those of the [[Phanerozoic]] eon, perhaps 7 to 10 times today's levels.<ref name=Kah2007>{{cite journal|first=L. C.|last=Kah|first2=R.|last2=Riding|year=2007|title=Mesoproterozoic carbon dioxide levels inferred from calcified cyanobacteria|journal=Geology|volume=35|issue=9|pages=799\u2013802|doi=10.1130/G23680A.1|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f7e26bb7a9aee8909f9d583c86ea3d4daa7a4609}}</ref> The first record of ice from this time period was reported in 2020 from the 1 Ga Scottish [[Diabaig Formation]] in the [[Torridon Group]], where [[dropstone]] formations were likely formed by debris from [[ice rafting]]; the area, then situated between [[35th parallel south|35]]\u2013[[50th parallel south|50]]\u00b0S, was a (possibly upland) lake which is thought to have frozen over in the winter and melted in the summer, rafting occurring in the spring melt.<ref>{{cite journal|first=A.|last=Hartley|first2=B.|last2=Kurjanski|first3=J.|last3=Pugsley|first4=J.|last4=Armstrong|year=2020|title=Ice-rafting in lakes in the early Neoproterozoic: dropstones in the Diabaig Formation, Torridon Group, NW Scotland|journal=Scottish Journal of Geology|doi=10.1144/sjg2019-017}}</ref>\n\nA higher abundance of other greenhouse gases, namely methane produced by prokaryotes, may have compensated for the low CO<sub>2</sub> levels; a largely ice-free world may have been achieved with a methane concentration of 140 [[parts per million]] (ppm).<ref name=Kah2007/><ref name=Fiorella2017/> However, [[methanogenic]] prokaryotes could not have produced so much methane, implying some other greenhouse gas, probably [[nitrous oxide]], was elevated, perhaps to 3 ppm (10 times today's levels). Based on presumed greenhouse gas concentrations, equatorial temperatures during the Mesoproterozoic may have been about {{cvt|295\u2013300|K|C F}}, in the tropics {{cvt|290|K|C F}}, at 60\u00b0 {{cvt|265\u2013280|K|C F}}, and the poles {{cvt|250\u2013275|K|C F}};<ref>{{cite journal|first=M. T.|last=Hren|first2=N. D.|last2=Sheldon|year=2020|title=Terrestrial microbialites provide constraints on the mesoproterozoic atmosphere|journal=The Depositional Record|volume=6|pages=4\u201320|doi=10.1002/dep2.79}}</ref> and the global average temperature about {{cvt|19|C|F}}, which is 4&nbsp;\u00b0C (7.2&nbsp;\u00b0F) warmer than today. Temperatures at the poles were estimated to have dropped below freezing in winter, allowing for temporary sea ice formation and snowfall, but there were likely no permanent ice sheets.<ref name=Peng2019>{{cite journal|first=L.|last=Peng|first2=L.|last2=Yonggang|first3=H.|last3=Yongyun|first4=Y.|last4=Yun|first5=S. A.|last5=Pisarevsky|year=2019|title=Warm Climate in the \"Boring Billion\" Era|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=93|pages=40\u201343|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.14239}}</ref>\n\nIt has also been proposed that, because the intensity of [[cosmic ray]]s has been shown to be positively correlated to cloud cover, and cloud cover reflects light back out into space and reduces global temperatures, lower rates of bombardment during this time due to reduced star formation in the galaxy caused less cloud cover and stayed glaciation events, maintaining a warm climate.<ref name=Veizer2005>{{Cite journal|title = Celestial Climate Driver: A Perspective from Four Billion Years of the Carbon Cycle|url = https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/GC/article/view/2691|journal = Geoscience Canada|year=2005 |df=dmy-all |issn = 1911-4850|volume = 32|issue = 1|first = J.|last = Veizer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Shaviv| first = Nir J.| year=2003 |df=dmy-all| title = The spiral structure of the Milky Way, cosmic rays, and ice age epochs on Earth| journal = New Astronomy| volume = 8| issue = 1| pages = 39\u201377| doi = 10.1016/S1384-1076(02)00193-8| arxiv = astro-ph/0209252| bibcode = 2003NewA....8...39S}}</ref> Also, some combination of weathering intensity which would have reduced CO<sub>2</sub> levels by oxidation of exposed metals, cooling of the [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] and reduced [[geothermal heat]] and volcanism, and increasing solar intensity and solar heat may have reached an equilibrium barring ice formation.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nConversely, glacial movements over a billion years ago may not have left many remnants today, and an apparent lack of evidence could simply be due to the incompleteness of the fossil record rather than absence. Further, the low oxygen and solar intensity levels may have prevented the formation of the [[ozone layer]], preventing [[greenhouse gas]]ses from being trapped in the atmosphere and heating the Earth via the [[greenhouse effect]], which would have caused glaciation.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Glacio-epochs and the supercontinent cycle after \u223c 3.0&nbsp;Ga: Tectonic boundary conditions for glaciation|journal = Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|year=2008 |df=dmy-all |pages = 89\u2013129|volume = 258|issue = 1\u20132|doi = 10.1016/j.palaeo.2007.09.021|first = N.|last = Eyles}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Palaeoclimates: the first two billion years|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|year=2006 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 1868609|pmid = 16754607|pages = 917\u2013929|volume = 361|issue = 1470|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2006.1839|first = J. F.|last = Kasting|first2 = S.|last2 = Ono}}</ref> However, not much oxygen is necessary to sustain the ozone layer, and levels during the Boring Billion may have been high enough for it,<ref>{{cite book|first=D. C.|last=Catling|first2=J. F.|last2=Kasting|year=2017|title=Atmospheric Evolution on Inhabited and Lifeless Worlds|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=291|isbn=978-1-316-82452-8}}</ref> though the Earth may still have been more heavily bombarded by [[UV radiation]] than today.<ref name=Campesi2013/>\n\n==Oceanic composition==\nThe oceans seem to have had low concentrations of key nutrients thought to be necessary for complex life, namely [[molybdenum]], iron, [[nitrogen]], and [[phosphorus]], in large part due to a lack of oxygen and resultant [[oxidation]] necessary for these [[geochemical cycle]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Anbar| first = A. D.| last2 = Knoll| first2 = A. H.| year=2002 |df=dmy-all| title = Proterozoic Ocean Chemistry and Evolution: A Bioinorganic Bridge?| journal = Science| volume = 297| issue = 5584| pages = 1137\u20131142| doi = 10.1126/science.1069651| issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 12183619| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1137A| citeseerx = 10.1.1.615.3041}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| authorlink1=Katja Fennel| last = Fennel| first = K.| last2 = Follows| first2 = M| last3 = Falkowski| first3 = P. G.| year=2005| title = The co-evolution of the nitrogen, carbon and oxygen cycles in the Proterozoic ocean| journal = American Journal of Science| volume = 305| issue = 6\u20138| pages = 526\u2013545| doi = 10.2475/ajs.305.6-8.526| issn = 0002-9599| bibcode = 2005AmJS..305..526F}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=M. A.|last=Kipp|first2=E. E.|last2=St\u00fceken|year=2017|title=Biomass recycling and Earth's early phosphorus cycle|journal=Science Advances|volume=3|issue=11|pages=eaao4795|doi=10.1126/sciadv.aao4795|pmid=29202032|pmc=5706743}}</ref> However, nutrients were more abundant in terrestrial environments, such as lakes or nearshore environments closer to continental runoff.<ref name=Parnell2015>{{cite journal|first=J.|last=Parnell|first2=S.|last2=Sprinks|first3=S.|last3=Andrews|first4=W.|last4=Thayalan|first5=S.|last5=Bowden|year=2015|title=High Molybdenum availability for evolution in a Mesoproterozoic lacustrine environment|journal=Nature Communications|volume=6|issue=6996|pages=6996|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/276921766|doi=10.1038/ncomms7996|pmid=25988499}}</ref>\n\nIn general, the oceans may have had an oxygenated surface layer, a sulfidic middle layer,<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\"/> and suboxic bottom layer.<ref name=Slack2009/><ref name=DeBaar1988/> The predominantly sulfidic composition may have caused the oceans to be a black- and milky-turquoise color instead of blue.<ref>{{cite journal|first=V. A.|last=Gallardo|first2=C.|last2=Espinoza|year=2008|title=Evolution of ocean color|journal=Proceedings of the International Society for Optical Engineering|volume=7097|pages=1\u20137|doi=10.1117/12.794742|bibcode=2008SPIE.7097E..0GG|url=https://www.comlsecretariat.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/Gallardo-Espinoza-paper-on-the-evolution-of-ocean-color.pdf|series=Instruments, Methods, and Missions for Astrobiology XI|editor1-last=Hoover|editor1-first=Richard B|editor2-last=Levin|editor2-first=Gilbert V|editor3-last=Rozanov|editor3-first=Alexei Y|editor4-last=Davies|editor4-first=Paul C}}</ref>\n\n===Oxygen===\n[[File:Evolution Of Atmosferic Oxygen.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Partial pressure]], in [[standard atmosphere (unit)|atm]], of atmospheric oxygen over the last 3.85 Ga (upper and lower estimates)]]\nEarth's geologic record indicates two events associated with significant increases in oxygen levels on Earth, with one occurring between 2.4 and 2.1 Gya, known as the Great Oxygenation Event, and the second occurring an approximate 0.8&nbsp;Ga.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|title = Oxygen fluctuations stalled life on Earth|year=2014|first=Jane|last=Qiu|url = http://www.nature.com/news/oxygen-fluctuations-stalled-life-on-earth-1.15529|journal = Nature|access-date = 2017-02-24 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1038/nature.2014.15529}}</ref> The intermediary period, during the Boring Billion, is thought have had low oxygen levels (with minor fluctuations), leading to widespread [[anoxic waters]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|title = The rise of oxygen in Earth's early ocean and atmosphere|year=2014|journal = Nature|pages = 307\u2013315|volume = 506|issue = 7488|doi = 10.1038/nature13068|pmid=24553238|first = Timothy W.|last = Lyons|first2 = Christopher T.|last2 = Reinhard|first3 = Noah J.|last3 = Planavsky|bibcode = 2014Natur.506..307L}}</ref>\n\nThe oceans may have been distinctly stratified, with surface water oxygenated,<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\"/> and deep water suboxic (less than 1 [[micromolar|\u03bcM]] oxygen),<ref name=DeBaar1988>{{cite journal|last=De Baar|first=H. J. W.|last2=German|first2=C. R.|last3=Elderfield|first3=H|last4=van Gaans|first4=P.|year=1988|title=Rare earth element distributions in anoxic waters of the Cariaco Trench|journal=Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta|volume=52|issue=5|pages=1203\u20131219|doi=10.1016/0016-7037(88)90275-X}}</ref> the latter possibly maintained by lower levels of [[hydrogen]] (H<sub>2</sub>) and H<sub>2</sub>S output by deep sea [[hydrothermal vent]]s which otherwise would have been chemically reduced by the oxygen.<ref name=Slack2009/> The [[decomposition]] of sinking organic matter would have also leeched oxygen from deep waters.<ref name=Johnston2009/><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe sudden drop in O<sub>2</sub> after the Great Oxygenation Event\u2014indicated by [[\u03b413C]] levels to have been loss of 10 to 20 times the current volume of atmospheric oxygen\u2014is known as the [[Lomagundi Excursion Event]], and is the most prominent [[Isotopes of carbon|carbon isotope]] event in Earth's history.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Large-scale fluctuations in Precambrian atmospheric and oceanic oxygen levels from the record of U in shales|journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date = 2013-05-01 |df=dmy-all |pages = 284\u2013293|volume = 369\u2013370|doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2013.03.031|first = C. A.|last = Partin|first2 = A.|last2 = Bekker|first3 = N. J.|last3 = Planavsky|first4 = C. T.|last4 = Scott|first5 = B. C.|last5 = Gill|first6 = C.|last6 = Li|first7 = V.|last7 = Podkovyrov|first8 = A.|last8 = Maslov|first9 = K. O.|last9 = Konhauser|bibcode=2013E&PSL.369..284P}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Oxygen overshoot and recovery during the early Paleoproterozoic|journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date = 2012-02-01 |df=dmy-all |pages = 295\u2013304|volume = 317\u2013318|doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2011.12.012|first = A.|last = Bekker|first2 = H. D.|last2 = Holland|bibcode=2012E&PSL.317..295B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Rise in seawater sulphate concentration associated with the Paleoproterozoic positive carbon isotope excursion: evidence from sulphate evaporites in the \u223c2.2\u20132.1 Gyr shallow-marine Lucknow Formation, South Africa|journal = Terra Nova|date = 2008-04-01 |df=dmy-all |issn = 1365-3121|pages = 108\u2013117|volume = 20|issue = 2|doi = 10.1111/j.1365-3121.2008.00795.x|language = en|first = S.|last = Schr\u00f6der|first2 = A.|last2 = Bekker|first3 = N. J.|last3 = Beukes|first4 = H.|last4 = Strauss|first5 = H. S.|last5 = Van Niekerk|bibcode = 2008TeNov..20..108S}}</ref> Oxygen levels may have been less than 0.1 to 2% of modern-day levels, which would have effectively stalled the evolution of complex life during the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Oxic conditions would have become dominant at the second oxygenation event causing the proliferation of [[Aerobic organism|aerobic]] activity over [[Anaerobic organism|anaerobic]],<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=Johnston2009/> but widespread suboxic and anoxic conditions likely lasted until about 0.55 Gya corresponding with [[Ediacaran biota]] and the [[Cambrian explosion]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=L. C.|last=Kah|first2=T. W.|last2=Lyons|first3=T. D.|last3=Frank|year=2004|title=Low marine sulphate and protracted oxygenation of the Proterozoic biosphere|journal=Nature|volume=438|issue=7010|pages=834\u2013838|doi=10.1038/nature02974|pmid=15483609|url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/geosciencefacpub/99}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=L. M.|last=Och|first2=G. A.|last2=Shields-Zhou|year=2012|title=The Neoproterozoic oxygenation event: Environmental perturbations and biogeochemical cycling|journal=Earth-Science Reviews|volume=110|issue=1\u20134|pages=26\u201357|doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2011.09.004}}</ref>\n\n===Sulfur===\n[[File:How oceans become euxinic.png|thumb|upright=2|Diagram of how [[euxinic]] conditions form]]\nIn 1998, geologist [[Donald Canfield]] proposed what is now known as the [[Canfield ocean]] hypothesis. Canfield claimed that increasing levels of oxygen in the atmosphere at the Great Oxygenation Event would have reacted with and oxidized continental [[iron pyrite]] (FeS<sub>2</sub>) deposits, with [[sulfate]] (SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup>) as a byproduct, which was transported into the sea. [[Sulfate-reducing microorganisms]] converted this to [[hydrogen sulfide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S), dividing the ocean into a somewhat oxic surface layer, and a sulfidic layer beneath, with [[anoxygenic photosynthesis|anoxygenic]] bacteria living at the border, metabolizing the H<sub>2</sub>S and creating sulfur as a waste product. This created widespread [[euxinic]] conditions in middle-waters, an anoxic state with a high sulfur concentration, which was maintained by the bacteria.<ref name=Canfield1998/><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Lyons| first = Timothy W.| last2 = Reinhard| first2 = Christopher T.| year=2009 |df=dmy-all| title = An early productive ocean unfit for aerobics| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume = 106| issue = 43\n |pages = 18045\u201318046| doi = 10.1073/pnas.0910345106| issn = 0027-8424| pmc = 2775325| pmid = 19846788| bibcode = 2009PNAS..10618045L}}</ref><ref name=Canfield1998>{{Cite journal| last = Canfield| first = D. E.\n| year=1998|df=dmy-all| title = A new model for Proterozoic ocean chemistry| journal = Nature| volume = 396| issue = 6710| pages = 450\u2013453| doi = 10.1038/24839| issn = 0028-0836| bibcode = 1998Natur.396..450C}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Biodiversity and Earth History|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ct29BwAAQBAJ|publisher = Springer|date = 2015-03-31|isbn = 9783662463949|language = en|first = Jens|last = Boenigk|first2 = Sabina|last2 = Wodniok|first3 = Edvard|last3 = Gl\u00fccksman}}</ref><ref name=Johnston2009>{{Cite journal|title = Anoxygenic photosynthesis modulated Proterozoic oxygen and sustained Earth's middle age|last = Johnston|first = D. T. |year=2009 |journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|doi = 10.1073/pnas.0909248106 |pmid = 19805080|pmc = 2753640|volume=106|issue = 40|pages=16925\u201316929|bibcode =2009PNAS..10616925J}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Large|first2=J. A.|last2=Halpin|first3=L. V.|last3=Danyushevsky|year=2014|title=Trace element content of sedimentary pyrite as a new proxy for deep-time ocean\u2013atmosphere evolution|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=389|pages=209\u2013220|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2013.12.020}}</ref>\n\n===Iron===\nAmong rocks dating to the Boring Billion, there is a conspicuous lack of [[banded iron formation]]s, which form from iron in the upper water column reacting with oxygen and precipitating out of the water, with the iron deriving from the deep sea. They seemingly cease around the world after 1.85 Ga. Canfield said that oceanic SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2\u2212</sup> [[redox|reduced]] all the iron in the anoxic deep sea, as opposed to oxygen as previously supposed.<ref name=Canfield1998/> Iron could have been metabolized by anoxygenic bacteria.<ref name=Canfield2018/> It has also been proposed that the 1.85 Ga [[Sudbury Basin|Sudbury meteor impact]] mixed the previously stratified Canfield ocean via tsunamis, interaction between vaporized seawater and the oxygenated atmosphere, oceanic [[cavitation]], and massive runoff of destroyed [[continental margin]]s into the sea. Resultant suboxic deep waters (due to oxygenated surface water mixing with previously anoxic deep water) would have oxidized deep-water iron, preventing it from being transported and deposited on continental margins.<ref name=Slack2009>{{cite journal|first=J. F.|last=Slack|first2=W. F.|last2=Cannon|year=2009|title=Extraterrestrial demise of banded iron formations 1.85 billion years ago|journal=Geology|volume=37|issue=11|pages=1011\u20131014|doi=10.1130/G30259A.1}}</ref>\n\nNonetheless, iron-rich (ferrous) waters did exist, such as the 1.4 Ga [[Xiamaling Formation]] of Northern China, which perhaps was fed by deep water hydrothermal vents. Ferrous conditions also indicate anoxic bottom water in this area, as oxic conditions would have oxidized all the iron.<ref name=Canfield2018>{{cite journal|first=D. E.|last=Canfield|authorlink=Donald Canfield|first2=S.|last2=Zhang|first3=H.|last3=Wang|first4=X.|last4=Wang|first5=W.|last5=Zhao|first6=J.|last6=Su|first7=C. J.|last7=Bjerrum|first8=E. R.|last8=Haxen|first9=E. U.|last9=Hammarlund|year=2018|title=A Mesoproterozoic iron formation|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=17|pages=3895\u20133904|doi=10.1073/pnas.1720529115|pmid=29632173|pmc=5924912}}</ref>\n\n==Lifeforms==\nLow nutrient abundance may have caused increased [[symbiosis|photosymbiosis]]\u2014where one organism is capable of photosynthesis and the other metabolizes the waste product\u2014among [[prokaryote]]s ([[bacteria]] and [[archaea]]), and the emergence of [[eukaryote]]s. Bacteria, Archaea, and Eukaryota are the three [[domain (biology)|domains]], the highest taxonomic ranking. Eukaryotes are distinguished from prokaryotes by a [[cell nucleus|nucleus]] and membrane-bound organelles, and all multicellular organisms are eukaryotes.<ref name=Brasier1998>{{cite journal|first=M. D.|last=Brasier|first2=J. F.|last2=Lindsay|year=1998|title=A billion years of environmental stability and the emergence of eukaryotes: new data from northern Australia|journal=Geology|volume=26|issue=6|pages=555\u2013558|doi=10.1130/0091-7613(1998)026<0555:ABYOES>2.3.CO;2|pmid=11541449}}</ref>\n\n===Prokaryotes===\n[[File:Stromatolites, Belt Supergroup, Glacier National Park.jpg|thumb|1.44 Ga [[stromatolite]] from [[Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Glacier National Park]], Montana]]\nProkaryotes were the dominant lifeforms throughout the Boring Billion.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=Gueneli/><ref name=Canfield1998/> Anoxygenic cyanobacteria are thought to have been the dominant photosynthesizers, metabolizing the abundant H<sub>2</sub>S in the oceans. However, in iron-rich waters, cyanobacteria may have suffered from [[iron poisoning]], especially in offshore waters were iron-rich deep water mixed with surface waters, and were outcompeted by other bacteria which could metabolize both iron and H<sub>2</sub>S. However, iron poisoning could have been abated by [[silica]]-rich waters or [[biomineralization]] of iron within the cell.<ref name=Javaux2018>{{cite journal|first=E. J.|last=Javaux|first2=K.|last2=Lepot|year=2018|title=The Paleoproterozoic fossil record: Implications for the evolution of the biosphere during Earth's middle-age|journal=Earth-Science Reviews|volume=176|pages=68\u201386|doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2017.10.001}}</ref>\n\n[[Microfossil]]s indicate the presence of cyanobacteria, [[green sulfur bacteria|green]] and [[purple sulfur bacteria|purple]] sulfur bacteria, methane-producing archaea or bacteria, sulfate-metabolizing bacteria, [[methanotroph|methane-metabolizing]] archaea or bacteria, iron-metabolizing bacteria, [[denitrifying bacteria|nitrogen-metabolizing]] bacteria, and anoxygenic photosynthetic bacteria.<ref name=Javaux2018/>\n\n===Eukaryotes===\nEukaryotes may have arisen around the beginning of the Boring Billion,<ref name=Mukherjee2018/> coinciding with the accretion of Columbia, which could have somehow increased oceanic oxygen levels.<ref name=Brooke2014/> However, multicellular eukaryotes possibly already evolved by this time, with the earliest claimed fossil evidence dating to the Great Oxygenation Event with jellyfish-like [[Francevillian biota]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=A.|last=El Albani|first2=S.|last2=Bengtson|first3=D. E.|last3=Canfield|authorlink3=Donald Canfield|first4=A.|last4=Bekkler|year=2010|title=Large colonial organisms with coordinated growth in oxygenated environments 2.1 Gyr ago|journal=Nature|volume=466|issue=7302|pages=100\u2013104|doi=10.1038/nature09166|pmid=20596019|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/44902514}}</ref> Following this, eukaryotic evolution was rather slow,<ref name=\":10\" /> possibly due to the euxinic conditions of the Canfield ocean and a lack of key nutrients and metals<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=Mukherjee2018/> which prevented large, complex life with high energy requirements from evolving.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|title = Low Mid-Proterozoic atmospheric oxygen levels and the delayed rise of animals|journal = Science|date = 2014-10-31 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0036-8075|pmid = 25359975|pages = 635\u2013638|volume = 346|issue = 6209|doi = 10.1126/science.1258410|language = en|first = Noah J.|last = Planavsky|first2 = Christopher T.|last2 = Reinhard|first3 = Xiangli|last3 = Wang|first4 = Danielle|last4 = Thomson|first5 = Peter|last5 = McGoldrick|first6 = Robert H.|last6 = Rainbird|first7 = Thomas|last7 = Johnson|first8 = Woodward W.|last8 = Fischer|first9 = Timothy W.|last9 = Lyons|bibcode = 2014Sci...346..635P|url = https://authors.library.caltech.edu/50325/13/Planavsky.SM.pdf}}</ref> Euxinic conditions would have also decreased the solubility of iron<ref name=Canfield1998/> and [[molybdenum]],<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Reinhard| first = C. T.| last2 = Planavsky| first2 = N. J.| last3 = Robbins| first3 = L. J.| last4 = Partin| first4 = C. A.| last5 = Gill| first5 = B. C.| last6 = Lalonde| first6 = S. V.| last7 = Bekker| first7 = A.| last8 = Konhauser| first8 = K. O.| last9 = Lyons| first9 = T. W.| year=2013|df=dmy-all | title = Proterozoic ocean redox and biogeochemical stasis| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume = 110| issue = 14| pages = 5357\u20135362| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1208622110| issn = 0027-8424| pmc = 3619314| pmid = 23515332| bibcode = 2013PNAS..110.5357R}}</ref> essential metals in [[nitrogen fixation]]. A lack of dissolved nitrogen would have favored prokaryotes over eukaryotes, as the former can metabolize gaseous nitrogen.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal| last = Anbar| first = A. D.| year=2002 |df=dmy-all | title = Proterozoic ocean chemistry and evolution: a bioinorganic bridge| journal = Science| volume = 297| issue = 5584| pages = 1137\u20131142| doi = 10.1126/science.1069651| pmid = 12183619| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1137A}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ramathallus lobatus.png|thumb|left|upright|1.6 Ga ''[[Ramathallus]]'' fossil, the earliest known [[red alga]]<ref name=Bengtson2017/>]]\nNonetheless, the diversification of [[crown group]] eukaryotic macroorganisms seems to have started about 1.6\u20131 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=S.|last=Bengtson|first2=V.|last2=Belivanova|first3=B.|last3=Rasmussen|first4=M.|last4=Whitehouse|year=2009|title=The controversial \"Cambrian\" fossils of the Vindhyan are real but more than a billion years older|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=106|issue=19|pages=7729\u20137734|doi=10.1073/pnas.0812460106|pmid=19416859|pmc=2683128}}</ref> seemingly coinciding with an increase in key nutrient concentrations.<ref name=Mukherjee2018/> According to phylogenetic analysis, plants diverged from animals and fungi about 1.6 Gya; animals and fungi about 1.5 Gya; [[Bilateria]]ns and [[cnidaria]]ns (animals respectively with and without [[bilateral symmetry]]) about 1.3 Gya; [[sponge]]s 1.35 Gya;<ref name=Hedges2004/> and [[Ascomycota]] and [[Basidiomycota]] (the two divisions of the fungus [[subkingdom]] [[Dikarya]]) 0.97 Gya.<ref name=Hedges2004/> The earliest known [[red algae]] mats date to 1.6 Gya.<ref name=Bengtson2017>{{cite journal|first=S.|last=Bengtson|first2=T.|last2=Sallstedt|first3=V.|last3=Belivanova|first4=M.|last4=Whitehouse|year=2017|title=Three-dimensional preservation of cellular and subcellular structures suggests 1.6 billion-year-old crown-group red algae|journal=PLOS Biology|volume=15|issue=3|page=e2000735|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.2000735|pmc=5349422|pmid=28291791}}</ref> The earliest known fungus dates to 1.01\u20130.89 Gya from Northern Canada.<ref name=Loron2019>{{cite journal|first=C. C.|last=Loron|first2=C.|last2=Fran\u00e7ois|first3=R. H.|last3=Rainbird|first4=E. C.|last4=Turner|first5=S.|last5=Borensztajn|first6=E. J.|last6=Javaux|year=2019|title=Early fungi from the Proterozoic era in Arctic Canada|journal=Nature|volume=70|pages=232\u2013235|issue=7760|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333301933|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1217-0|pmid=31118507}}</ref> Multicellular eukaryotes had probably evolved about 2\u20131.4 Gya, thought to be the descendants of colonial unicellular aggregates.<ref>{{cite book|first=G. M.|last=Cooper|year=2000|chapter=The Origin and Evolution of Cells|title=The Cell: A Molecular Approach|edition=2nd|publisher=Sinauer Associates|chapter-url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9841/}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Niklas|first=K. J.|year=2014|title=The evolutionary-developmental origins of multicellularity|journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=101|issue=1|pages=6\u201325|doi=10.3732/ajb.1300314|pmid=24363320}}</ref> Likewise, early multicellular eukaryotes likely mainly aggregated into [[stromatolite]] mats.<ref name=Brooke2014>{{cite book|first=J. L.|last=Brooke|year=2014|title=Climate Change and the Course of Global History: A Rough Journey|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=40\u201342|isbn=978-0-521-87164-8}}</ref>\n\nThe 1.2 Ga red alga ''[[Bangiomorpha]]'' is the earliest known sexually reproducing and [[meiosis|meiotic]] lifeform,<ref>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285932986 |chapter=DNA Repair as the Primary Adaptive Function of Sex in Bacteria and Eukaryotes |pages=1\u201349 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202307/https://www.novapublishers.com/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=31918# |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead|last1=Bernstein|first1=H.|last2=Bernstein|first2=C.|last3=Michod|first3=R. E.|editor1-last=Kimura| editor1-first=S.|editor2-last=Shimizu|editor2-first=S.|publisher=Nova Biomedical|isbn=978-1-62100-756-2|title=DNA Repair: New Research|date=2012}}</ref> and, based on this, these adaptations evolved 2\u20131.4 Gya.<ref name=Mukherjee2018>{{cite journal|first=I.|last=Mukherjee|first2=R. R.|last2=Large|first3=R.|last3=Corkrey|first4=L. V.|last4=Danyushevsky|year=2018|title=The Boring Billion, a slingshot for Complex Life on Earth|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=4432|pages=4432|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-22695-x|pmid=29535324|pmc=5849639}}</ref> However, these may have evolved well before the last common ancestor of eukaryotes given that meiosis is performed using the same proteins in all eukaryotes, perhaps stretching to as far back as the hypothesized [[RNA world]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=R.|last=Egel|first2=D.|last2=Penny|year=2007|title=On the Origin of Meiosis in Eukaryotic Evolution: Coevolution of Meiosis and Mitosis from Feeble Beginnings|journal=Genome Dynamics and Stability|volume=3|issue=249\u2013288|pages=249\u2013288|doi=10.1007/7050_2007_036|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226518084|isbn=978-3-540-68983-6}}</ref>\n\nCell [[organelle]]s probably originated from free-living [[cyanobacteria]] ([[symbiogenesis]])<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{cite journal |title=Endosymbiotic gene transfer: organelle genomes forge eukaryotic chromosomes|journal=Nature Reviews Genetics|year=2004|pages=123\u2013135|volume=5|issue=2|doi=10.1038/nrg1271|first=J. N.|last=Timmis|first2=Michael A.|last2=Ayliffe|first3=C. Y.|last3=Huang|first4=W.|last4=Martin|pmid=14735123}}</ref><ref name=Mukherjee2018/> possibly after the evolution of [[phagocytosis]] (engulfing other cells) with the removal of the rigid [[cell wall]] which was only necessary for asexual reproduction.<ref name=\":10\" /> [[Mitochondria]] had already evolved in the Great Oxygenation Event, but [[plastid]]s used in plants for namely [[photosynthesis]] are thought to have appeared about 1.6\u20131.5 Gya.<ref name=Hedges2004>{{cite journal|first=S. B.|last=Hedges|first2=J. E.|last2=Blair|first3=M. L.|last3=Venturi|first4=J. L.|last4=Shoe|year=2004|title=A molecular timescale of eukaryote evolution and the rise of complex multicellular life|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=4|issue=2|pages=2|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-4-2|pmc=341452|pmid=15005799}}</ref> [[Histone]]s likely appeared during the Boring Billion to help organize and package the increasing amount of DNA in eukaryotic cells into [[nucleosome]]s.<ref name=\":10\" /> [[Hydrogenosome]]s used in anaerobic activity may have originated in this time from an archaeon.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|title = Energy metabolism among eukaryotic anaerobes in light of Proterozoic ocean chemistry|journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|date = 2008-08-27 |df=dmy-all |issn = 0962-8436|pmc = 2606767|pmid = 18468979|pages = 2717\u20132729|volume = 363|issue = 1504|doi = 10.1098/rstb.2008.0031|language = en|first = Marek|last = Mentel|first2 = William|last2 = Martin}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal| last = Martin| first = W.| last2 = M\u00fcller| first2 = M.| year=1998 |df=dmy-all| title = The hydrogen hypothesis for the first eukaryote| journal = Nature| volume = 392| issue = 6671| pages = 37\u201341| doi = 10.1038/32096| issn = 0028-0836| pmid=9510246| bibcode = 1998Natur.392...37M}}</ref>\n\nGiven the evolutionary landmarks achieved by eukaryotes, this time period could be considered an important precursor to the Cambrian explosion about 0.54 Gya, and the evolution of relatively large, complex life.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Ecology===\nDue to the marginalization of large food particles, such as algae, in favor of cyanobacteria and prokaryotes which do not transmit as much energy to higher [[trophic level]]s, a complex [[food web]] likely did not form, and large lifeforms with high energy demands could not evolve. Such a food web probably only sustained a small number of [[protist]]s as, in a sense, [[apex predator]]s.<ref name=Gueneli>{{cite journal|first=N.|last=Gueneli|first2=A. M.|last2=McKenna|first3=N.|last3=Ohkouchi|first4=C. J.|last4=Boreham|first5=J.|last5=Beghin|first6=E. J.|last6=Javaux|first7=J. J.|last7=Brocks|year=2018|title=1.1-billion-year-old porphyrins establish a marine ecosystem dominated by bacterial primary producers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=115|issue=30|pages=6978\u20136986|doi=10.1073/pnas.1803866115|pmid=29987033|pmc=6064987}}</ref>\n\nThe presumably oxygenic photosynthetic eukaryotic [[acritarch]]s, perhaps a type of [[microalga]], inhabited the Mesoproterozoic surface waters.<ref>{{cite journal|first=M.|last=Moczydlowska|first2=E.|last2=Landing|first3=W.|last3=Zang|first4=T.|last4=Palacios|year=2011|title=Proterozoic phytoplankton and timing of Chlorophyte algae origins|journal=Palaeontology|volume=54|issue=4|pages=721\u2013733|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4983.2011.01054.x}}</ref> Their population may have been largely limited by nutrient availability rather than predation because species have been reported to have survived for hundreds of millions of years, but after 1 Gya, species duration dropped to about 100 Ma, perhaps due to increased herbivory by early protists. This is consistent with species survival dropping to 10 Ma just after the Cambrian explosion and the expansion of herbivorous animals.<ref>{{cite journal|first=S. M.|last=Stanley|year=2008|title=Predation defeats competition on the seafloor|journal=Paleobiology|volume=31|issue=1|page=12<!--only citing this page-->|doi=10.1666/07026.1}}</ref>\n\n===Life on land===\nSome of the earliest evidence of the prokaryotic colonization of land dates to before 3 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Homann|first=M.|display-authors=et al.|year=2018|title=Microbial life and biogeochemical cycling on land 3,220 million years ago|journal=Nature Geoscience|volume=11|issue=9|pages=665\u2013671|doi=10.1038/s41561-018-0190-9}}</ref> possibly as early as 3.5 Gya.<ref>{{cite journal|first=R. J.|last=Baumgartner|first2=M. J.|last2=van Kranendonk|display-authors=et al.|title=Nano\u2212porous pyrite and organic matter in 3.5-billion-year-old stromatolites record primordial life|journal=Geology|volume=47|issue=11|pages=1039\u20131043|year=2019|doi=10.1130/G46365.1}}</ref> During the Boring Billion, land may have been inhabited mainly by cyanobacterial mats.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Watanabe |first=Yumiko|last2=Martini |first2=Jacques E. J. |last3=Ohmoto |first3=Hiroshi |date=2000-11-30 |df=dmy-all |title=Geochemical evidence for terrestrial ecosystems 2.6 billion years ago |journal=Nature|volume=408 |issue=6812 |pages=574\u2013578 |doi=10.1038/35046052 |issn=0028-0836 |pmid=11117742 |bibcode=2000Natur.408..574W}}</ref><ref name=Horodyski1994>{{Cite journal |last=Horodyski |first=R. J. |last2=Knauth |first2=L. P. |year=1994 |df=dmy-all |title=Life on land in the precambrian |journal=Science |volume=263 |issue=5146 |pages=494\u2013498 |doi=10.1126/science.263.5146.494 |issn=0036-8075 |pmid=17754880 |bibcode=1994Sci...263..494H}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Retallack |first=Gregory J. |last2=Mindszenty |first2=Andrea |date=1994-04-01 |df=dmy-all |title=Well preserved late Precambrian Paleosols from Northwest Scotland |url=http://jsedres.geoscienceworld.org/content/64/2a/264 |journal=Journal of Sedimentary Research |language=en |volume=64 |issue=2a |pages=264\u2013281 |doi=10.1306/D4267D7A-2B26-11D7-8648000102C1865D |issn=1527-1404}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Horodyski| first = R. J.| last2 = Knauth| first2 = L. P.| year=1994 |df=dmy-all| title = Life on land in the precambrian| journal = Science| volume = 263| issue = 5146| pages = 494\u2013498| doi = 10.1126/science.263.5146.494| issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 17754880| bibcode = 1994Sci...263..494H}}</ref> Dust would have supplied an abundance of nutrients and a means of dispersal for surface-dwelling microbes, though microbial communities could have also formed in caves and freshwater lakes and rivers.<ref name=Campesi2013/><ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://risweb.st-andrews.ac.uk/portal/da/researchoutput/life-on-land-in-the-proterozoic-evidence-from-the-torridonian-rocks-of-northwest-scotland(b8c702c9-ba95-4ac8-b78c-84293f17881d).html |title=Life on land in the Proterozoic: Evidence from the Torridonian rocks of northwest Scotland |volume=30 |issue=9 |pages=811 |journal=Geology |year=2002 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(2002)030<0811:LOLITP>2.0.CO;2 |first=Anthony Robert |last=Prave |access-date=2016-03-05 |df=dmy-all |bibcode=2002Geo....30..811P}}</ref> By 1.2 Gya, microbial communities may have been abundant enough to have affected weathering, [[erosion]], sedimentation, and various geochemical cycles,<ref name=Horodyski1994/> and expansive microbial mats could indicate [[biological soil crust]] was abundant.<ref name=Campesi2013>{{cite journal|first=H.|last=Beraldi-Campesi|year=2013|title=Early life on land and the first terrestrial ecosystems|journal=Ecological Processes|volume=2|issue=1|pages=1\u201317|doi=10.1186/2192-1709-2-1}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest terrestrial eukaryotes may have been lichen fungi about 1.3 Ga,<ref name=Heckman2001>{{cite journal|first=D. S.|last=Heckman|first2=D. M.|last2=Geiser|first3=B. R.|last3=Eidell|first4=R. L.|last4=Stauffer|first5=N. L.|last5=Kardos|first6=S. B.|last6=Hedges|year=2001|title=Molecular Evidence for the Early Colonization of Land by Fungi and Plants|journal=Science|volume=293|issue=5532|pages=494\u2013498|doi=10.1126/science.263.5146.494|pmid=17754880}}</ref> which grazed on the microbial mats.<ref name=Campesi2013/> Abundant eukaryotic microfossils from the freshwater Scottish [[Torridon Group]] seems to indicate eukaryotic dominance in non-marine habitats by 1 Gya,<ref>{{cite journal|first=P. K.|last=Strother|first2=L.|last2=Battison|first3=M. D.|last3=Brasier|authorlink3=Martin Brasier|first4=C. H.|last4=Wellman|year=2011|title=Earth's earliest non-marine eukaryotes|journal=Nature|volume=473|issue=7348|pages=505\u2013509|doi=10.1038/nature09943|pmid=21490597|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/51048998}}</ref> probably due to increased nutrient availability in areas closer to the continents and continental runoff.<ref name=Parnell2015/> These lichen may have later facilitated plant colonization 0.75 Gya in some manner.<ref name=Heckman2001/> A massive increase in terrestrial photosynthetic biomass seems to have occurred about 0.85 Gya, indicated by a flux in terrestrially-sourced carbon, which may have increased oxygen levels enough to support an expansion of multicellular eukaryotes.<ref>{{cite journal|first=L. P.|last=Knauth|year=2009|title=The late Precambrian greening of the Earth|journal=Nature|volume=460|issue=7256|pages=728\u2013732|doi=10.1038/nature08213|pmid=19587681}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Precambrian}}\n*{{annotated link|Ediacaran biota}}\n*{{annotated link|Francevillian biota}}\n*{{annotated link|Snowball Earth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|first=M.|last=Brasier|year=2012|title=Secret Chambers: The Inside Story of Cells and Complex Life|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-964400-1|ref={{harvid|Brasier|2012}}}}\n\n[[Category:Proterozoic]]\n[[Category:Geological history of Earth]]\n", "name_user": "AhmadLX", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimatic stability:intense \u2192 luminous", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boring_Billion"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Wild Cat Creek", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Wild Cat Creek\n|partof=the [[War of 1812]]\n|image=Indiana Territory 1812.gif\n|image_size=220px\n|caption=\n|date=22 November 1812 \n|place=[[Wildcat Creek (Indiana)]]\n|result= Tribal American victory\n|combatant1=Indigenous Confederacy: <br/>[[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]]<br/>[[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]]<br/>[[Shawnee]]<br/>Supported by:<br> {{Flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|combatant2={{flag|United States|1795}}<br/>[[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry]]<br/>Kentucky Infantry<br/>[[Indiana Rangers]]\n|commander2=[[Samuel Hopkins (congressman)|Samuel Hopkins]]\nKumakskau Shawnee brother of Tecumseh in command\n|strength1=1,200\n|strength2=1,250\n|casualties1=none\n|casualties2=17 killed<br>3 wounded<ref name=Gilpin149>Gilpin, p. 149</ref>\n|campaignbox=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox War of 1812: Old Northwest}}\n\n'''The Battle of Wild Cat Creek''' was the result of a November 1812 [[punitive expedition]] against [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] villages during the [[War of 1812]]. It has been nicknamed \"'''Spur's Defeat'''\", which is thought to refer to the [[spur]]s used by the soldiers to drive their horses away from the battle as quickly as possible.  The campaign is sometimes referred to as the '''Second Battle of Tippecanoe'''.<ref name=Dyer>Dyer \u2013 link below</ref>\n\n==Second Tippecanoe campaign==\nFollowing several defeats and massacres in 1812, notably the [[Battle of Fort Dearborn|Fort Dearborn Massacre]] and the [[Pigeon Roost Massacre]], a joint punitive campaign was sent to [[Illinois Territory]] under the commands of Major General [[Samuel Hopkins (congressman)|Samuel Hopkins]] and Colonel [[William Russell (Kentucky)|William Russell]].  Russell, coming from the [[Siege of Fort Harrison]], led a force of Illinois militia and [[Indiana Rangers]], and [[Illinois Territory in the War of 1812|was successful]] in destroying a hostile Kickapoo village on [[Peoria Lake]].  Russell had to retreat to [[Cahokia]], however, when he could not locate the forces under Hopkins.  Hopkins could not get his Kentucky militia to engage, and had been driven back to [[Vincennes, Indiana|Vincennes]] when the Kickapoo started a [[Grass fire|prairie grass fire]].<ref>Allison, 192</ref>\n\nHopkins was humiliated by his loss, and discharged the Kentucky militia under his command.  He then raised a new army, consisting of three regiments of Kentucky Infantry, one company of the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry]] under Major [[Zachary Taylor]], a troop of Indiana Rangers, and a company of scouts.<ref name=A193>Allison, 193</ref>  Hopkins left Vincennes on 11 November 1812 and marched north, following the same route [[William Henry Harrison]] had taken in 1811.\n\nWhen the army reached the site of the [[Battle of Tippecanoe]], they found that some of the United States' dead had been [[Exhumation|exhumed]] and [[Scalping|scalped]]. The bodies were reburied before the army proceeded to [[Prophetstown State Park|Prophetstown]], which it reached on 19 November.<ref name=Dyer /> Prophetstown had been destroyed in the 1811 Battle of Tippecanoe, but was now partially rebuilt, with an even larger Kickapoo village nearby.<ref name=A193 />  All residents and provisions had been evacuated as the army approached. The army burned the villages to the ground.\n\nA [[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]] village was found nearby, on [[Wildcat Creek (Indiana)|Wildcat Creek]], and Hopkins decided to attack it.  Colonel Miller led 300 men and destroyed the evacuated village.<ref name=A194>Allison, 194</ref>  On November 21, as a scouting party explored the creek, they were fired upon, and the entire force retreated to rejoin the main army, leaving behind the body of a soldier named Dunn.\n\nThe next day, 22 November, Colonels Miller and Wilcox accompanied Captain Beckes and sixty Indiana Rangers to recover Dunn's body.<ref name=A194 />  After riding about six miles up Wildcat Creek, they found a dead comrade's head stuck on a pole and a Native standing beside the head taunting them.  Thirteen Indiana Rangers were outraged by this and chased the rider, but he managed to stay ahead of them, and led them into a narrow canyon.  Here, [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]], [[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]], and [[Shawnee]] warriors ambushed the Rangers.  Within two minutes, twelve men and several horses were dead or dying.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm |title=Spur\u2019s Defeat by Shawnee in November 1812 |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Ferguson, Rich |year=2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161158/http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm| archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Many of the officers were killed, and the Rangers fled.  One man who escaped did so by spurring his horse to gallop faster, hence the naming of the battle \"Spur's Defeat\".<ref name=Ferguson>{{cite web|url=http://media.wibc.com/av/audio/simpson/Rich_Ferguson_3-3.m3u|title=Indianapolis Tonight|last=Ferguson|first=Rich|date=March 3, 2008|publisher=WIBC|accessdate=2009-01-15}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livingplaces.com/IN/Tippecanoe_County/Perry_Township.html|title=Perry Township|last=Gombach|first=Julia|publisher=The Gombach Group |accessdate=2009-01-15}}</ref>\n\nOne man, Benoit Besayon, had been a long-time trader with the Indian villages in the area, and was captured alive in the canyon.  He was judged to be a traitor, and sentenced to be burned at the stake.  As the fire was lit, however, a friend took pity on him and shot him.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lasselle |first=Charles B |date=March 1906|title=The Old Indian Traders of Indiana |journal=The Indiana Magazine of History |volume=II |issue=1 |pages=8; 12 (f.n. 14) |publisher=George S. Cottman |location=Indianapolis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zpwKAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA1 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe American losses on November 21\u201322 were seventeen killed and three wounded.<ref name=Gilpin149/>\n\nScouts learned that a large force of Native Americans were gathering to fight Hopkins' army, and they prepared to do battle as soon as possible.  Bitter cold set in, however, and a snowstorm threatened the expedition.  When the Indian camp was reached on 24 November, it was deserted.<ref name=Dyer />  Hopkins turned back, stopping at [[Fort Harrison, Indiana|Fort Harrison]] to recover from the weather before proceeding to Vincennes.  By the time they reached [[Forts of Vincennes, Indiana|Fort Knox]], two hundred men were suffering from sickness or [[frostbite]].<ref name=A195>Allison, 195</ref>  Hopkins became so depressed from his successive losses that he resigned.<ref name=A195 /> Hopkins was brought before a Court of Inquiry for his actions in the [[Illinois Territory]] and Prophetstown.  He was cleared of any wrongdoing by the military tribunal and later ran for the Senate.\n\n==Modern investigations==\n\nAlthough it has been claimed there was no significant importance to this battle, General William Henry Harrison's military operational plan reflects the overall importance of the expedition. Hopkin's mission was twofold. First, he wanted to drive the hostile Kickapoos to Canada in response to the Fort Dearborn Massacre. Second, he wanted to burn Prophetstown again to drive the Aboriginal Confederacy also towards Canada and out of the Northwest Territories. Hopkin's men encountered 200 mounted Indian warriors which they had never experienced before. This and the weather were the two factors that drove Hopkin's expedition back to Fort Harrison.\n\nThe actual site of this esoteric American defeat is unknown.  The Carroll County Historical Association has erected a historic marker at the intersection of W 550 S Rd. and S 800 W Rd. in the town of Pyrmont (40.4673532, -86.6800204)  noting that the site is \"in a nearby ravine\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ingenweb.org/intippecanoe/spurs.htm | title = Spur's Defeat Historical Marker}}</ref>.  Purdue University and Indiana State archaeologists and historians suggest that there is little scholarly interest in the site and the event because of its lack of importance.  Local amateur reenactment groups have taken an interest in commemorating the event.  However, the found site has been verified by archeologists donating their time to have found the skirmish site and possible burial location of the 18 men.\n<ref>''Hopkins Orderly Book'', Indiana Historical Society Library, Indianapolis, Indiana{{page needed|date=November 2014}}</ref><ref>Logan Essary Ph.D. (1915), ''A History of Indiana'', W. K. Stewart Co. (Indianapolis, Indiana), p. 196</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Allison, Harold |title=The Tragic Saga of the Indiana Indians |year=1986|publisher=Turner Publishing Company, Paducah |isbn=0-938021-07-9}}\n* Ferguson, Richard (2010), ''They Were Too Drunk with Firewater and Fear: A tale of the Northwest Operations Court of Inquiry of Kentucky Major General Samuel Hopkins September 1812 to April 1813'', Indiana Rangers Publishing Co. (North Manchester, Indiana). {{ISBN|9780615551999}}.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.ingenweb.org/intippecanoe/spurs.htm |title=Spur's Defeat |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Dyer, Adina |year=1998}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm |title=Spur\u2019s Defeat by Shawnee in November 1812 |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Ferguson, Rich |year=2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161158/http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm| archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= live}}\n\n{{Battles of the War of 1812}}\n{{Indiana in the War of 1812}}\n{{Kentucky in the War of 1812}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wild Cat Creek}}\n[[Category:Battles involving Native Americans]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of 1812 in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Battles in the Old Northwest]]\n[[Category:Zachary Taylor]]\n[[Category:November 1812 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Wild Cat Creek\n|partof=the [[War of 1812]]\n|image=Indiana Territory 1812.gif\n|image_size=220px\n|caption=\n|date=22 November 1812 \n|place=[[Wildcat Creek (Indiana)]]\n|result= Tribal American victory\n|combatant1=Indigenous Confederacy: <br/>[[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]]<br/>[[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]]<br/>[[Shawnee]]<br/>Supported by:<br> {{Flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|combatant2={{flag|United States|1795}}<br/>[[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry]]<br/>Kentucky Infantry<br/>[[Indiana Rangers]]\n|commander2=[[Samuel Hopkins (congressman)|Samuel Hopkins]]\nKumakskau Shawnee brother of Tecumseh in command\n|strength1=1,200\n|strength2=1,250\n|casualties1=none\n|casualties2=17 killed<br>3 wounded<ref name=Gilpin149>Gilpin, p. 149</ref>\n|campaignbox=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox War of 1812: Old Northwest}}\n\n'''The Battle of Wild Cat Creek''' was the result of a November 1812 [[punitive expedition]] against [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] villages during the [[War of 1812]]. It has been nicknamed \"'''Spur's Defeat'''\", which is thought to refer to the [[spur]]s used by the soldiers to drive their horses away from the battle as quickly as possible.  The campaign is sometimes referred to as the '''Second Battle of Tippecanoe'''.<ref name=Dyer>Dyer \u2013 link below</ref>\n\n==Second Tippecanoe campaign==\nFollowing several defeats and massacres in 1812, notably the [[Battle of Fort Dearborn|Fort Dearborn Massacre]] and the [[Pigeon Roost Massacre]], a joint punitive campaign was sent to [[Illinois Territory]] under the commands of Major General [[Samuel Hopkins (congressman)|Samuel Hopkins]] and Colonel [[William Russell (Kentucky)|William Russell]].  Russell, coming from the [[Siege of Fort Harrison]], led a force of Illinois militia and [[Indiana Rangers]], and [[Illinois Territory in the War of 1812|was successful]] in destroying a hostile Kickapoo village on [[Peoria Lake]].  Russell had to retreat to [[Cahokia]], however, when he could not locate the forces under Hopkins.  Hopkins could not get his Kentucky militia to engage, and had been driven back to [[Vincennes, Indiana|Vincennes]] when the Kickapoo started a [[Grass fire|prairie grass fire]].<ref>Allison, 192</ref>\n\nHopkins was humiliated by his loss, and discharged the Kentucky militia under his command.  He then raised a new army, consisting of three regiments of Kentucky Infantry, one company of the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry]] under Major [[Zachary Taylor]], a troop of Indiana Rangers, and a company of scouts.<ref name=A193>Allison, 193</ref>  Hopkins left Vincennes on 11 November 1812 and marched north, following the same route [[William Henry Harrison]] had taken in 1811.\n\nWhen the army reached the site of the [[Battle of Tippecanoe]], they found that some of the United States' dead had been [[Exhumation|exhumed]] and scalped. The bodies were reburied before the army proceeded to [[Prophetstown State Park|Prophetstown]], which it reached on 19 November.<ref name=Dyer /> Prophetstown had been destroyed in the 1811 Battle of Tippecanoe, but was now partially rebuilt, with an even larger Kickapoo village nearby.<ref name=A193 />  All residents and provisions had been evacuated as the army approached. The army burned the villages to the ground.\n\nA [[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]] village was found nearby, on [[Wildcat Creek (Indiana)|Wildcat Creek]], and Hopkins decided to attack it.  Colonel Miller led 300 men and destroyed the evacuated village.<ref name=A194>Allison, 194</ref>  On November 21, as a scouting party explored the creek, they were fired upon, and the entire force retreated to rejoin the main army, leaving behind the body of a soldier named Dunn.\n\nThe next day, 22 November, Colonels Miller and Wilcox accompanied Captain Beckes and sixty Indiana Rangers to recover Dunn's body.<ref name=A194 />  After riding about six miles up Wildcat Creek, they found a dead comrade's head stuck on a pole and a Native standing beside the head taunting them.  Thirteen Indiana Rangers were outraged by this and chased the rider, but he managed to stay ahead of them, and led them into a narrow canyon.  Here, [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]], [[Ho-Chunk|Winnebago]], and [[Shawnee]] warriors ambushed the Rangers.  Within two minutes, twelve men and several horses were dead or dying.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm |title=Spur\u2019s Defeat by Shawnee in November 1812 |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Ferguson, Rich |year=2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161158/http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm| archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Many of the officers were killed, and the Rangers fled.  One man who escaped did so by spurring his horse to gallop faster, hence the naming of the battle \"Spur's Defeat\".<ref name=Ferguson>{{cite web|url=http://media.wibc.com/av/audio/simpson/Rich_Ferguson_3-3.m3u|title=Indianapolis Tonight|last=Ferguson|first=Rich|date=March 3, 2008|publisher=WIBC|accessdate=2009-01-15}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livingplaces.com/IN/Tippecanoe_County/Perry_Township.html|title=Perry Township|last=Gombach|first=Julia|publisher=The Gombach Group |accessdate=2009-01-15}}</ref>\n\nOne man, Benoit Besayon, had been a long-time trader with the Indian villages in the area, and was captured alive in the canyon.  He was judged to be a traitor, and sentenced to be burned at the stake.  As the fire was lit, however, a friend took pity on him and shot him.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lasselle |first=Charles B |date=March 1906|title=The Old Indian Traders of Indiana |journal=The Indiana Magazine of History |volume=II |issue=1 |pages=8; 12 (f.n. 14) |publisher=George S. Cottman |location=Indianapolis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zpwKAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA1 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe American losses on November 21\u201322 were seventeen killed and three wounded.<ref name=Gilpin149/>\n\nScouts learned that a large force of Native Americans were gathering to fight Hopkins' army, and they prepared to do battle as soon as possible.  Bitter cold set in, however, and a snowstorm threatened the expedition.  When the Indian camp was reached on 24 November, it was deserted.<ref name=Dyer />  Hopkins turned back, stopping at Fort Harrison to recover from the weather before proceeding to Vincennes.  By the time they reached [[Forts of Vincennes, Indiana|Fort Knox]], two hundred men were suffering from sickness or [[frostbite]].<ref name=A195>Allison, 195</ref>  Hopkins became so depressed from his successive losses that he resigned.<ref name=A195 />\nHopkins was brought before a Court of Inquiry for his actions in the Ill. Territory and Prophetstown.  He was cleared of any wrongdoing by the military tribunal and later ran for the Senate.\n\n==Modern investigations==\n\nAlthough it has been claimed there was no significant importance to this battle, General William Henry Harrison's military operational plan reflects the overall importance of the expedition. Hopkin's mission was twofold. First, he wanted to drive the hostile Kickapoos to Canada in response to the Fort Dearborn Massacre. Second, he wanted to burn Prophetstown again to drive the Aboriginal Confederacy also towards Canada and out of the Northwest Territories. Hopkin's men encountered 200 mounted Indian warriors which they had never experienced before. This and the weather were the two factors that drove Hopkin's expedition back to Fort Harrison.\n\nThe actual site of this esoteric American defeat is unknown.  The Carroll County Historical Association has erected a historic marker at the intersection of W 550 S Rd. and S 800 W Rd. in the town of Pyrmont (40.4673532, -86.6800204)  noting that the site is \"in a nearby ravine\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ingenweb.org/intippecanoe/spurs.htm | title = Spur's Defeat Historical Marker}}</ref>.  Purdue University and Indiana State archaeologists and historians suggest that there is little scholarly interest in the site and the event because of its lack of importance.  Local amateur reenactment groups have taken an interest in commemorating the event.  However, the found site has been verified by archeologists donating their time to have found the skirmish site and possible burial location of the 18 men.\n<ref>''Hopkins Orderly Book'', Indiana Historical Society Library, Indianapolis, Indiana{{page needed|date=November 2014}}</ref><ref>Logan Essary Ph.D. (1915), ''A History of Indiana'', W. K. Stewart Co. (Indianapolis, Indiana), p. 196</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Allison, Harold |title=The Tragic Saga of the Indiana Indians |year=1986|publisher=Turner Publishing Company, Paducah |isbn=0-938021-07-9}}\n* Ferguson, Richard (2010), ''They Were Too Drunk with Firewater and Fear: A tale of the Northwest Operations Court of Inquiry of Kentucky Major General Samuel Hopkins September 1812 to April 1813'', Indiana Rangers Publishing Co. (North Manchester, Indiana). {{ISBN|9780615551999}}.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.ingenweb.org/intippecanoe/spurs.htm |title=Spur's Defeat |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Dyer, Adina |year=1998}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm |title=Spur\u2019s Defeat by Shawnee in November 1812 |accessdate=11 January 2009 |author=Ferguson, Rich |year=2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161158/http://www.warof1812.ca/spurdefeat.htm| archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= live}}\n\n{{Battles of the War of 1812}}\n{{Indiana in the War of 1812}}\n{{Kentucky in the War of 1812}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wild Cat Creek}}\n[[Category:Battles involving Native Americans]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War of 1812 in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Battles in the Old Northwest]]\n[[Category:Zachary Taylor]]\n[[Category:November 1812 events]]\n", "name_user": "Canute", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSecond Tippecanoe campaign:misc cleanup, add links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Wild_Cat_Creek"}
